<HEAD>Lawyer Says NHTSA Seat Belt Probe Is `Back Burner' Maneuver</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal regulators hope to put on `` the back burner'' claims that some <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> seat belts can cause crippling injuries, an attorney representing a paraplegic child's family alleges The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> opened an investigation Wednesday into 1.7 million Ford Escort and Mercury Lynx cars to determine if the rear seat belts are safe. The agency turned down a request by the child's family that the cars be recalled immediately. `` Everything I know tells me that study on top of study means finesse,'' said <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakayan </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> attorney for the family of <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON>, who was crippled at age 11 in the 1985 crash of a Ford Escort. `` It puts it on the back burner for awhile.'' He accused the agency of seeking to placate congressional critics while deferring action on the issue until after the next president is inaugurated. <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> in January filed a petition for recall of the 1984-1988 cars on behalf of the child's parents, <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> and <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> of <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plata </LOCATION>, Md. The couple alleged a strap retainer caused the seat belt to ride around their child's waist rather than the hips. When the car in which they were riding smashed head-on into a tractor-trailer, the seat belt cut through the soft tissue to their son's spine, they said. The Garretts in January won a $ 3.3 million judgment against <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> for their child's injuries. <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> said in a letter to the <ORGANIZATION> Garretts </ORGANIZATION>' attorneys that a limited technical review had left the agency `` unable to conclude that the strap retainer has had an adverse effect on the performance of the system.'' The agency said the Lynx and Escort seat belts met federal safety standards, but added, `` Testing did indicate that the ... rear safety belts with and without the strap retainer fit differently on test subjects compared to rear safety belts in some other cars.'' The agency ordered a mid-level investigation, an engineering analysis, to probe the safety effects of the belts' fit. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said it believes the belts are safe. `` They meet or exceed all federal motor vehicle safety standard performance requirements, including those for location, fit, strength and ease of use,'' <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said. `` We are confident that the agency, too, will conclude that no safety-related defect is involved,'' <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said. In the 1985 accident, near <LOCATION> Annapolis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, a second back-seat passenger, 14-year-old <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaboury </PERSON>, was killed. The two front-seat occupants were hospitalized after the accident but escaped crippling injury, even though the passenger compartment crumpled in the collision. The accident and subsequent lawsuit prompted public questioning of the safety of rear-seat safety belts, particularly those with the unusual design found in the Escort and <ORGANIZATION> Lynx </ORGANIZATION>. Belts that ride against the hips are braced on a large mass of bone in an accident, keeping the passenger anchored while avoiding damage to the spine. Belts that ride above the hip under the impact of a crash can slice through the body's soft tissue to the spine, resulting in paralysis or death. <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> said its strong recommendation that seat belts be used remains unchanged. `` Whether it be at the front or the rear, ... you are far better off wearing any kind of belt than no belt at all, and that is based on studies of hundreds of thousands of accidents and fatalities and injuries,'' said <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> DeFore </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman.
