<SECOND>PM-Treasury Auction,90</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yields on Five-Year Notes Hit 9.04 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Yields on five-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> notes rose in the latest auction to the highest level since late 1985. The average yield Wednesday was 9.04 percent, up from 8.77 percent at the last auction on May 26. It was the highest rate since five-year notes averaged 9.13 percent on Nov. 27, 1985. The notes will carry a coupon interest rate of 9 percent, with each $ 10,000 in face value selling for $ 9,975.90. A total of $ 7.27 billion in notes was sold out of bids totaling $ 21.57 billion.
