<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rival presidential candidates <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> are saying they want to debate this fall but sound far from agreement on when or where or how often they will meet. `` Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will debate his opponent this fall,'' said a brief statement Wednesday from the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign. But the announcement also said it was `` unlikely that a debate can occur prior to Sept. 20.'' That brought an outraged reaction from <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON>, who accused the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign of `` seeking to unilaterally reject'' debates scheduled for Sept. 8 in <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, and Sept. 14, in <LOCATION> Annapolis </LOCATION>, Md. <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign decision not to accept the earlier dates `` threatens the full schedule of debates anticipated for the fall. It is a transparent effort to limit the number of debates.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, during a stop in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, said flatly, `` I'm going to be in <LOCATION> Annapolis </LOCATION> on the 14th with or without him.'' The <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION> debate is being sponsored by the League of Women Voters, the <LOCATION> Annapolis </LOCATION> forum by the bipartisan <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Presidential Debates. A <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spokesman said that while the Republican presidential nominee had said long ago he would debate his Democratic opponent, he had never agreed to any specific events. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> is expected to meet with <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> next week to negotiate the debate format. The campaign statement said they would discuss `` sponsorship, timing, ground rules and other related matters.'' The announcement said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aides were confident `` the two campaigns would be able to work out the details of the debate schedule between themselves.'' It also said the campaign `` thanked the groups and organizations which had offered to help expedite the process.'' <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> retorted: `` Mr. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> stated that the campaign is not prepared for a debate prior to Sept. 20. This is inexcusable. The presidential commission debates have been scheduled for over a year and the vice president has known he would be his party's nominee for more than five months. ... `` The <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people have a right to the full schedule of these debates as agreed upon by the two national political parties.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> added during a campaign stop in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>: `` After seven years of on-the-job training, it seems to me that he ought to be able to go to work and debate the issues. ... The vice president has been saying a lot about defense and national security, and I'm ready to debate him. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign spokesman <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodin </PERSON> said: `` There were never any commitments made on specifics of a debate schedule. We've been very specific in saying the vice president wants to debate Governor <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>.''
