<SECOND>PM-US-Soviet Grain,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>US, Soviets Agree to Extend Grain Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> have agreed tentatively to extend their grain deal for another year while trying to complete a new, longer-range accord, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official says. The official, who asked not to be identified, said Wednesday that the two countries agreed through diplomatic channels last week on an extension that is essentially identical to the current pact. A second official insisted that no final agreement had been reached, but said he believed that one could be completed shortly. `` We feel like we made some progress, but we're still far apart on pricing, minimums and things of that nature,'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Kay </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said of the first three U.S.-Soviet negotiating sessions. <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> said the two countries are trying to schedule a fourth meeting. `` I'm optimistic at the next session we'll reach an agreement,'' he said. Under the current five-year pact, which expires Sept. 30, the Soviets must buy at least 9 million tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grain annually. The grain deal benefits American farmers, now experiencing severe drought problems, and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, which often looks to the West for grain even though it has had a good harvest this year. Last month, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> estimated that the Soviets would have a bumper harvest of 215 million metric tons, which would be their third best crop ever. The Soviets are importing grain to build up their stockpiles and to feed expanding livestock herds. The Soviets already have been given permission to purchase more than 12 million tons of grain for this year. As of last month, they had bought more than 5 million tons of corn, more than 9 million tons of wheat, 830,700 tons of soybeans and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal.
