<HEAD>Deputy Police Chief Resigns As Commissioner Blasts Park
Supervision</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 12th graf `Wodarski was' with five grafs to UPDATE with
details of report, reassignment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A deputy police chief resigned under fire Wednesday as the police commissioner issued a report blaming him and other brass for a riot at a park that led to 100 complaints of police brutality. Deputy Chief <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Darcy </PERSON>, a 31-year police veteran, commanded hundreds of police officers who were deployed to defuse a demonstration at Tompkins Square Park on <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Lower </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION> on Aug. 6. The demonstration _ against a 1 a.m. curfew at the park _ turned violent and more than 50 people were hurt in clashes between police and protesters. More than 100 charges of police brutality were later filed with the Civilian Complaint Review Board. Commissioner <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>'s report said a lack of supervision was responsible for `` the appalling behavior of some members of the department.'' `` The control of the situation was lost during the first confrontation between police and demonstrators and never sufficiently regained,'' wrote Chief of Department <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, who prepared the 16-page report. `` For this Chief <PERSON> Darcy </PERSON>, the highest-ranking member of the department at the scene, must be held accountable.'' The other two supervisory officers at the confrontation, Deputy Inspector <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Wodarski </PERSON> and Capt. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON>, also were disciplined. <PERSON> Wodarski </PERSON> was the ranking officer at the scene during a crucial period when <PERSON> Darcy </PERSON> returned to his office about a dozen blocks away to go to the bathroom, but he deferred all major decisions to <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON>. `` Unfortunately,'' the report said, `` Capt. <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON>'s actions were not well planned, staffed, supervised or executed. Unnecessary confrontations resulted, which culminated in a riot.'' A key mistake, according to <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, was <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON>'s decision, at the beginning of the demonstration, to transmit an emergency signal that mobilized 300 police officers from all over the city without making any provisions for adequate supervision of the officers. Even after <PERSON> Darcy </PERSON> returned to the park, the mobilization call was never taken off the air. As a result, officers continued to pour into the area, further confusing the situation, <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Wodarski </PERSON> was reassigned from his prestigious post as commanding officer of the Midtown South Precinct to another, as a command in <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>. <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON> will be temporarily removed from his job commanding the 9th Precinct for a six - to seven-month retraining period, <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said During that time, the East Village Precinct house will be placed under the command of Inspector <PERSON> Elson </PERSON> <PERSON> Gelfand </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Civilian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Complaint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> has already identified several officers involved in the melee, relying in part on videotapes taken by neighborhood residents. The videotapes show police officers, some of whom covered or removed their badges, striking demonstrators for no apparent reason. The board recommended that charges be brought against two officers, both of whom were placed on modified assignment Wednesday pending outcome of a departmental trial. <PERSON> Darcy </PERSON>, 56, had been criticized anonymously shortly after the riot when <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> cited the decision by the ranking officer at the park to leave the scene to go to the bathroom at a crucial moment. The commissioner had said that was one of 10 mistakes that led to the melee. <PERSON> Darcy </PERSON> was trained in crowd control during the 1960s as a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Tactical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> was widely praised in those years for developing tactics that helped the city avoid the wide-scale civil disorder that plagued many other big cities.
