<HEAD>Drawing Machine Fails During Broadcast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE GEISSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> lotto machine that selects winning numbers jammed Wednesday night during a drawing for a $ 38 million jackpot, one of the nation's largest gambling windfalls. Lottery officials, following disaster recovery guidelines, hastily conducted another televised drawing a half hour after the regular time. `` There are procedures to handle this sort of thing and they were followed,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, the lottery's top spokesman at <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> headquarters. The first, incomplete drawing was ruled invalid, <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said. A drawing announcer called out the number 33 during the initial drawing but no ball bearing the number rolled out of the machine. At the outset of the second drawing, the announcer said, `` We've reloaded the machine and are beginning a new drawing. The reason the device failed was still being investigated, lottery officials said. It was the first failure in the 22-month history of the game. Before the first drawing, Californians were grabbing $ 1 lotto tickets at an estimated average rate of more than 500 a second. `` The lines are unreal. People who normally buy $ 5 worth of tickets are buying $ 20 worth,'' said <LOCATION> Anaheim </LOCATION> liquor store owner <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Notery </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON> `` Anybody with money to spend is thinking, nothing ventured, nothing gained.'' The fast pace of sales left lottery officials unsure of the exact jackpot total. Officials expected to determine Thursday whether there was a winner, and verify that person's identity later. If nobody picked the correct six numbers out of a choice of 49 numbers, the jackpot will be added to Saturday's drawing, said officials.
