<HEAD>Mayor Circumvents Prison Board Disapproval Of Condom Distribution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE LLOYD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mayor <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> <PERSON> Goode </PERSON> circumvented the city prison board and ordered condoms distributed to inmates as part of an AIDS prevention program in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> jails. On Monday, the board voted 3-2 with one abstention against making condoms available to prisoners, despite pleas from health officials and testimony from an inmate suffering from the deadly disease. <PERSON> Goode </PERSON> said Wednesday his program, which takes effect Sept. 1, also includes anonymous AIDS testing, counseling and treatment of prisoners. Prison board member <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendel </PERSON>, an attorney who strongly opposes distributing condoms, said <PERSON> Goode </PERSON> had the prerogative to circumvent the board. <PERSON> Mendel </PERSON> said he opposed the proposal because the law prohibits sex between prisoners. `` We're sending mixed signals,'' he said. He also said he doubted that prisoners will use the condoms, especially in cases of rape. `` A prisoner with AIDS is an animal'' who would not care whether his sex partner has protection from the disease, <PERSON> Mendel </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Mendel </PERSON> said only eight prisoners in the city's jails have been diagnosed as having acquired immune deficiency syndrome, indicating that `` prisons are not AIDS factories.'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Fair </PERSON>, director of AIDS programs for the city <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, said earlier this week that two prisoners have died from the disease. He said the number of prisoners infected with the AIDS virus would be difficult to estimate but could total more than half of the 3,700 in custody. During a two-hour discussion before Monday night's vote, <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON> urged approval of the policy, saying sexual activity was rampant in the city's jails. `` We are not condoning sexual activity,'' <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON> said. `` We are saying it is taking place ... and the best protection against AIDS is using a condom.''
