 Five Justice officials, along with <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> _ who resigned Aug. 12 and is now a private citizen _ plan to attend a similar legal conference in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> between Aug. 29-Sept. 1 `` What we basically said was that we are not going to challenge anything on the <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> trip, but here is guidance for the <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> trip,'' <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> said. The Justice employees who are traveling to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> are <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Korten </PERSON>, the department's chief spokesman; <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Rule </PERSON>, assistant attorney general for antitrust; <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> of the liaison office; <PERSON> Cheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Nolan </PERSON>, one of <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>' subordinates, and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Abell </PERSON>, director of the office of Justice programs. Mrs. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> is not scheduled to go on the trip, a secretary in <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>' office said. <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Burstion-Wade </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman, said the conference is designed to explore legal and economic relations between <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
