<HEAD>Costa-Gavras Has Made Career of Rubbing Nerves</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Marketing Betrayed, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 French director <PERSON> Costa-Gavras </PERSON> admits he has a knack for hitting sensitive nerves with his films about political repression, but he's fascinated by what he sees as dualism in American society. His latest movie, `` Betrayed,'' examines racist paramilitary groups in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and is likely to come under siege itself for its depiction of hard-working Midwestern farmers who lead a double life as racist killers. `` As an outsider, that's what fascinates me _ and confuses me _ about this country,'' the 55-year-old director said in a recent interview. `` You have racism here, especially against outsiders, yet you can have a presidential candidate who is Greek boy with a Jewish wife. `` You have worked so hard to fight totalitarianism and keep your democracy, yet your government supports dictators.'' <PERSON> Costa-Gavras </PERSON> also filmed `` Missing,'' about a right-wing dictatorship in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>. Conservative columnist <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Will </PERSON> called the story about a young American who disappeared during the coup that brought Gen. <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> to power `` a fraud'' and `` a hit' n run act of cowardice.'' In `` State of Siege,'' an earlier film shot in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> during the regime of Marxist president <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Costa-Gavras </ORGANIZATION> offended the left wing. The <ORGANIZATION> Chilean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> refused to cooperate in making the film, and pro-communist actors quit during the filming, claiming the movie was pro-CIA. `` You have to understand that people of my generation thought we knew the truth _ the only right way. We learned the hard way that it was n't so easy,'' said the Greek-born <PERSON> Costa-Gavras </PERSON>, who now lives in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. `` So when I make movies, I feel it's absolutely important to be critical of everyone. I do n't accept everyone's ideology automatically.''
