<SECOND>PM-Destitute Author,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Graduate' Author Nearly Destitute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 His 1962 novel `` The Graduate'' became a smash-hit movie evoking the discontent of a generation fed up with materialism. Today, however, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> finds himself looking for a handout. `` The things he stands for and believes in are principles he ca n't live by any longer,'' said <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>'s ex-wife <PERSON> Fred </PERSON>, who has accompanied him through two itinerant decades that has left the couple virtually homeless. <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>, 49, says his abhorrence of material things led him to give away two houses during the good times. He says he is nearly destitute, living out of a van on a few thousand dollars a year. `` It's hard to make anybody believe the author of ` The Graduate' needs money,'' he said Wednesday <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> said hard times have driven him and his 48-year-old ex-wife out of the southern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> campground where they lived for the past decade to the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> town where <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> went to college 30 years ago. He came East, he said, in hopes of finding a publisher for his latest project, a compilation of writings on prejudice. His plight, however, has taken him to the welfare office in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Adams </LOCATION>, which rejected him because he has no permanent address. The novelist, whose hero in `` The Graduate,'' <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Braddock </PERSON>, struck a chord among young readers with his post-graduate misery at his parents' suburban home, has lived until now according to what friends consider impossibly high and even self-destructive standards. `` If he's hard up for dough, it's obviously due to ... his inclination toward divestiture,'' said <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, who graduated with <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> from <ORGANIZATION> Williams </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in 1961 and teaches at the private <ORGANIZATION> Commonwealth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. He said the couple's tendency to rid themselves of property explains why they gave their <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> house to a real estate agent in the 1960s and a home to the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Audubon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> in 1970, when, <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> said, he felt the need for `` getting free of things.'' After the <ORGANIZATION> Webbs </ORGANIZATION>' marriage in 1962 in <PERSON> Fred </PERSON>'s posh hometown of <LOCATION> Lakeville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, they sold their wedding gifts at a yard sale, many of them to the guests who had given them. A yearning to be free also explains their decision to divorce eight years ago, although they had no intention of separating. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON>, an artist whom <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> met when she was a student at <ORGANIZATION> Bennington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>, said the couple felt marriage was a violation of their constitutional right to freedom. <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>, the son of a well-to-do <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> doctor, espoused odd views back in college, <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said. `` We always used to wonder whether <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> was putting us on,'' he said. `` He's quite sophisticated, a very intelligent person with a real heart, but he always said things that sounded peculiarly simple.'' <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> was the envy of classmates with the publication of `` The Graduate,'' which he wrote after his own graduation in a small apartment in <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION> that he rented with the help of a college creative writing grant. The obscure 1962 novel was catapulted to fame by the movie, and <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> was declared a highly gifted writer with a keen ear for dialogue. `` The Graduate'' was followed by four other novels, including `` The Marriage of A Young Stockbroker,'' which also was made into a movie. His last work, `` Booze,'' was published in 1978. <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> says he received only $ 20,000 for the film rights to `` The Graduate,'' which starred <PERSON> Dustin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>, in the days before authors insisted on a percentage of the movie's sales. The novel, however, is still in print and continues to earn a few thousand dollars in royalties annually. But he does n't regret the unusual life that led to his dilemma. `` It's hard to think there would be another way to do it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
