<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--AcidRain     08-25 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Acid Rain,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Evidence of Recovery From Acid Rain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists who built a 1,400-square-yard roof to shield the ground from acid rain reported today their experiment gives new hope that lakes and streams can recover when such pollution stops. Acid rain, which results from certain kinds of man-made pollution, can harm fish, other aquatic life, vegetation, buildings and monuments. For the experiment, begun in 1984 and reported in the British journal <ORGANIZATION> Nature </ORGANIZATION>, Norwegian and Swedish researchers built the roof over a site in southern <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> that had been exposed to acid rain. Precipitation that fell on the roof was filtered to remove acid-rain components, then distributed beneath the roof by sprinklers. Analysis showed the runoff beneath the roof began to recover normal chemistry after the structure was built. That `` indicates that chemical changes caused by acid deposition are largely reversible,'' the researchers wrote. The results agree with previous studies from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, they said. Further studies of soil and runoff will be needed to see if they can completely recover from acid rain, they said.
</TEXT>
