<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s government on Thursday freed the country's top dissident and nine others arrested in a crackdown by former hard-line President <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON>. A day earlier, the new president lifted martial law in the capital and called for a referendum on multiparty democracy. Those released included this correspondent, who on the drive home from Insein Jail saw for the first time in 26 years people shouting for democracy without any official hindrance. People of all ages, wearing red headbands symbolizing defiance, road in open trucks around the capital shouting, `` Give us democracy immediately!'' Banners hung across the roads said: `` We want democracy! We want a multiparty system!'' On Wednesday, President <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>, beseiged by mass street protests, said the ruling party soon will hold an emergency congress to consider popular demands for an end to authoritarian rule. <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>, in power for only a week, is the country's first civilian leader since military-dominated, one-party rule was instituted in 1962. This correspondent was arrested during July 29-30 raids that also netted leading dissident <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> Gyi </PERSON> and others. The official government News Agency of <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> accused them of `` attacking the state.'' The demonstrations that led to <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON>'s ouster after just 17 days in office left 112 people dead by official count and led to martial law being imposed in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>. A tourist said people danced in the streets of the capital on Wednesday when <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> ended martial law, ordered troops from the city center and lifted curfews throughout the country. <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s first civilian leader in 26 years, called for a popular vote on restoring multiparty democracy and said his government would resign if the ruling party rejects his plan. `` General elections will be held as soon as possible'' if the people approve a multiparty system, and no top government officials will run, the president said. <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> noted that Ne Win, who led the 1962 military coup that began authoritarian one-party rule in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>, proposed a referendum on multiparty government when he resigned July 23 but that members of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Burma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> rejected the proposal. The party leadership will meet again in the next month to consider the referendum again, he said. State-run <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rangoon </ORGANIZATION> said the party will meet Sept. 12. `` If the congress refuses to hold a referendum, I and ... the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Executive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> will resign from the party,'' said <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>, one of 14 members of the committee. If the party congress approves the idea of a referendum, the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, or parliament, will meet the next day and `` arrangements will be made to hold a national referendum in the quickest time possible,'' he said. If the people then approve a multiparty system, the Constitution will be amended, the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> will be dissolved and general elections will be held as soon as possible, he said. `` Neither I nor any personnel of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministers </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justices </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Attorneys </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> Inspectors will run in those elections,'' the president said. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> welcomes `` this movement toward democracy.'' But a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official who spoke on condition of anonymity said protesters want a clear announcement that elections will be held within a week or two, not a process that could take months. Ne Win, a former general, organized the military-dominated party in 1962. In 1964, he outlawed all other parties and began pursuing the rigid socialism and international isolation that turned one of <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>'s wealthiest nations into one of its poorest. When he resigned last month as chairman of the 1.1 million-member party, <PERSON> Ne </PERSON> <PERSON> Win </PERSON>, 77, cited his age and accepted indirect responsibility for bloody student-led riots against his government in March and June. He said then that the rioting `` showed the lack of trust and confidence in the government'' and called for a referendum on multiparty government. The rallies Wednesday, the third straight day of mass anti-government protest, attracted `` from several hundred thousand to up to 1 million'' people in the capital city of 3.5 million, a <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> diplomat said. When the radio announced martial law was lifted, `` the soldiers started to immediately pull up the barbed wire barricades, pull them away and retreat,'' <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Lubin </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> attorney traveling as a tourist, said after reaching <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>. `` The crowd immediately began to gravitate toward Sule pagoda and the town hall. People were dancing in the streets, shouting, ` We have won,''' said <PERSON> Lubin </PERSON>, 26. He said monks threw water on each other in a traditional celebration. `` A few of the soldiers were beginning to crack smiles at the people,'' he said. `` They seemed much more relaxed.'' No violence was reported. Diplomats said the demonstrators marched along main streets in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> and dispersed after five or six hours. About 5,000 people sat outside the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy listening to <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> writers, lawyers, doctors and other professionals speak over loudspeakers, a <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> diplomat said. The demonstrators sent frequent messages to the embassy asking for publicity and moral support, he said.
