<HEAD>Police Isolate Mines, But Strikers Stay Determined</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JASTRZEBIE, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As authorities tried to shut them off from the outside world, striking coal miners communicated through a clandestine network of couriers and listened in the dark to radio reports of the standoff. Provisions in stores in <LOCATION> Jastrzebie </LOCATION>, a southern mining city of 100,000, dwindled after the strikes began Aug. 16, with cheese and fresh meat virtually disappearing from the shelves. But food still reached the strikers. Farmers donated food and funds for the strikers and on Wednesday, 330 pounds of fresh pork arrived from Solidarity supporters in <LOCATION> Bialystok </LOCATION>, a city 335 miles away near the Soviet border. The police presence at the July Manifesto mine increased dramatically when more than 30 police vehicles took up positions at the main gate. A few hours later, 103 police vehicles, including an armored personnel carrier, jeeps, trucks and three water cannons, rolled through the city in the direction of another mine. The road leading to July Manifesto, where the leaders of the <LOCATION> Silesian </LOCATION> mine strikes set up headquarters, was sealed off by an army roadblock. A nightime curfew took effect Tuesday. Residents were ordered off the street from 11 p.m. to 5 a.m. to `` preserve the peace,'' according to signs posted throughout the city. The miners helped organize an effective network of couriers to relay messages among the striking mines and through a strike information center in the city's <ORGANIZATION> Blessed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virgin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. Police detained at least two couriers and accused them of speculating in bread and butter Wednesday. The two later were released and immediately resumed their rounds at the mines. Strikers resolved to continue their occupation until they won legalization of Solidarity and better wages. `` There are fewer people, but they are in an excited mood and they will stay to the end,'' said a regional Solidarity leader who visited several mines Wednesday. Not all the town's attention focused on the strike. Mothers in <LOCATION> Jastrzebie </LOCATION> were busy buying school supplies and new clothes for children who return to school Sept. 1. Those items take a big bite out of the family budget. A new school bag costs the equivalent of $ 4.50, or a miner's wages for a full day. At the church, a group of students from universities in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION> typed newsletters and communiques. They put the latest word on strikes around the country on a blackboard, and flags of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> were pinned on a map of the country to mark strike locations. In between radio news bulletins, students listen to the Doors and other old rock groups. At least two mines, July Manifesto and 30 Years of People's <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, printed daily strike newsletters on the premises On Tuesday, 125 miners at the latter mine descended 500 yards underground because they feared a police assault. On Wednesday, the miners decided to divide up shifts to have about 40 at time underground. Music soothed strained nerves, and whenever possible miners played cassettes over the loudspeakers. Still, according to the couriers inside the mines, radio news was the first priority. On the hour, strikers huddled together to listen to the latest news of the situaion of those who joined them in their struggle. They tuned by turns to Polish state radio, Radio Free <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the Polish-language service of the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>.
