<HEAD>Ali Gets Blood-Cleansing Treatment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HILTON HEAD ISLAND, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Muhammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> is receiving blood-cleansing treatments by a doctor who blames the former boxing champion's weakened condition on household pesticide poisoning and not blows to the head. The 46-year-old former heavyweight champion walked into a hospital waiting room throwing jabs in the air minutes after undergoing an eight-hour blood treatment to relieve the slurred speech and tremors that have plagued him in recent years. `` I feel like I can fight -LRB- heavyweight champ <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Tyson </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> said in a hoarse voice slightly above a whisper at <ORGANIZATION> Hilton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Head </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> referred questions to his physician, Dr. <PERSON> Rajko </PERSON> <PERSON> Medenica </PERSON>, an immunologist who specializes in cancer and blood disorders. <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> Hilton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Head </LOCATION> on Tuesday night to undergo plasmapheresis, during which his plasma was removed and replaced with an artificial product prepared by <PERSON> Medenica </PERSON>. Plasma is the yellowish fluid in which other components of the blood circulate in the body. Although <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> has been diagnosed as having parkinsonian syndrome, possibly brought on by blows to the head during his boxing career, <PERSON> Medenica </PERSON> disagrees. Calling it `` The Muhammad Ali Syndrome,'' he blamed household pesticide poisoning, which probably affected him so severely because of his rapid metabolism when he was in peak physical condition. <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> likely will return to Hilton Head for the treatments every three months or so, <PERSON> Medenica </PERSON> said. `` My goal is to remove the circulating toxins. By the end of the year, he should be much better,'' he said. Although <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> had trouble speaking, he moved with ease and appeared to be in good spirits. Moments after a brief question-and-answer session, he playfully pulled a small red handkerchief from his pocket and made it appear and disappear several times. `` I like to show people how easily they can be deceived,'' he said. <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> then performed other tricks, signed autographs and posed for photographs with delighted hospital workers. His wife, <PERSON> Lonnie </PERSON>, said that other than the slurred speech, <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> is doing better than many people realize. `` He feels no pain. He's never sick There is no hard part living with <PERSON> Muhammad </PERSON>. There is nothing special I have to do for him, except make sure he takes his medication.'' <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> called <PERSON> Medenica </PERSON> the greatest doctor in the world. `` He's got methods I've never seen before,'' he said.
