<HEAD>Police Chief Resigns As Commissioner Blasts Supervision During
Riot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The police chief in charge of hundreds of officers at a demonstration that turned into a riot resigned as the police commissioner released a scathing report blaming the violence on poor supervision. The report on Aug. 6's confrontation at <LOCATION> Tompkins </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> criticized Deputy Chief <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Darcy </PERSON>, 56, for a series of mistakes, beginning with his leaving the scene for about 90 minutes at a crucial time to use the bathroom. `` It was clear from the review that some police officers engaged in the excessive use of force against private citizens by striking demonstrators with nightsticks and kicking other apparently defenseless people,'' said Commissioner <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>. <PERSON> Darcy </PERSON>, a 31-year veteran who was the designated commander of the hundreds of officers deployed at the <LOCATION> Lower </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION> <LOCATION> park </LOCATION>, offered his resignation shortly before <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> released the report Wednesday. The two other supervisory officers at the confrontation, Deputy Inspector <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Wodarski </PERSON> and Capt. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON>, also were disciplined. Departmental charges also were brought against two other officers, and more were expected, <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said. The demonstration against enforcement of a 1 a.m. curfew that has since been suspended ended with injuries to more than 50 people, including passers-by. More than 100 charges of police brutality were filed. A police review board, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> and District Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgenthau </PERSON> are conducting separate investigations into the complaints. `` The control of the situation was lost during the first confrontation between police and demonstrators and never sufficiently regained,'' wrote Chief of Department <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> in the report. A key mistake, according to <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, was <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON>'s decision at the beginning of the demonstration to transmit an emergency signal that mobilized 300 officers from all over the city without making any provisions for adequate supervision. Other major errors included use of a low-flying helicopter with a search light, whose hovering presence acted as a magnet and drew people to the confrontation, and the premature decision to send police on horses into the crowd. <PERSON> Wodarski </PERSON> was reassigned from his prestigious post as commanding officer of the Midtown South Precinct to a command in <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>, but he did not lose his rank. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON> will be temporarily removed from his job commanding the a precinct for six to seven months of retraining. <PERSON> Darcy </PERSON> will receive a $ 55,000 annual pension. The police review board has identified several officers involved in the melee, relying in part on videotapes taken by neighborhood residents, and recommended charges against two. The commissioner noted that 17,000 of the department's 26,000 officers had been hired since 1980, and they, as well as their superiors, had no experience with riots. However, he said, `` The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is better than the events in <LOCATION> Tompkins </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> would have you think.'' Among the report's recommendations was a major training program in crowd control and policing of street disorders.
