<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION>'s bankruptcy trustee says he'll shorten the time the ministry has to sell its assets when he submits a revised reorganization plan to a bankruptcy judge who rejected his first proposal In rejecting the reorganization plan Wednesday, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Judge <PERSON> Rufus </PERSON> <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> said it failed to take into account the ministry's poor financial health. `` This plan does not work,'' <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> said. `` It does not reflect the situation.'' He gave <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> bankruptcy trustee M.C. `` Red'' <PERSON> Benton </PERSON> until Oct. 1 to prepare a new plan, and until Sept. 10 to return with information on potential buyers of the ministry's assets. <PERSON> Benton </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION>'s secured creditors rejected the plan because it allowed five years for the sale of the assets. <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION>'s major contributors, called lifetime partners, also rejected the plan, he said. <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> could have approved the plan despite the negative votes from creditors, but decided against it. Proceeds from the sale of assets would repay <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION>'s debts, which could top $ 130 million. <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> rejected the idea of closing down operations, saying that would kill <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION>'s revenue sources, which include donations from viewers of the televised ministry and proceeds from the <ORGANIZATION> Heritage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> retreat near <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mill </LOCATION>. The ministry, which entered bankruptcy proceedings in June 1987 after the resignation of founder <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> in a sex-and-money scandal, has been divided into the newly named <ORGANIZATION> Heritage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministries </ORGANIZATION> and a corporation holding <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION>'s assets. <PERSON> Benton </PERSON> said after the hearing that he would propose speeding up the time required for the sale of assets to six to seven months. <PERSON> Benton </PERSON> did not address the effect of the reorganization plan's rejection on potential buyers of the assets But he said setting a sale within seven months would let creditors know how much they would be receiving much quicker than the five years allowed in the original plan. <PERSON> Benton </PERSON> told the court the debtor corporation has been losing $ 400,000 a month, and needed $ 885,000 from the sale of other assets to survive 30 more days. Reynolds approved that request. <PERSON> Benton </PERSON> said he expected to have by a Sept. 1 a firm offer from <ORGANIZATION> Canadian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thomas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Samoth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to buy the <ORGANIZATION> Heritage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> theme park, satellite television network and other property. The company has offered $ 113 million for the network, park and 1,700 acres of undeveloped property. He said there also may be offers from <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, businessman <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shinn </PERSON> and an <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> group he declined to identify.
