<SECOND>PM-Singapore-Elections,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exchange Between Leader And Designated Successor Overshadows
Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Formal campaigning began today for next month's general elections, but the contest has been overshadowed by a public exchange between the only leader <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> has known and his designated successor The tension began in a three-hour speech Aug. 14, when Prime Minister <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuan </PERSON> <PERSON> Yew </PERSON> cited the shortcomings of Deputy Prime Minister <PERSON> Goh </PERSON> <PERSON> Chok </PERSON> <PERSON> Tong </PERSON>. On Monday, he suggested <PERSON> Goh </PERSON> see a psychiatrist. <PERSON> Goh </PERSON> said that <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> really meant a psychologist, and added that he planned to nudge the prime minister out of office, probably within two years. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said Monday that his deputy could not communicate as well on television and at mass meetings as he could in small groups. `` I do n't know why. I have suggested to him perhaps a bit of psychological adjustment, maybe a psychiatrist, something holds him back.'' <PERSON> Goh </PERSON> told reporters Tuesday that <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> suggested he consult a psychologist, `` not a psychiatrist, who is for mentally distressed people. `` I do not believe that a psychologist could help me. A speech therapist and trainer will, and I have been seeing my speech trainer for over a year,'' said <PERSON> Goh </PERSON>, who sometimes appears stiff and uneasy during televised speeches. `` I am not President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. I am not good at one-liners. Neither am I Prime Minister <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>. I am not good at making three-hour speeches.'' <PERSON> Goh </PERSON> quoted <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> as saying the prime minister `` is only waiting to be nudged out by a firm elbow. When the time comes, probably inside two years, I will gently nudge him out.'' <PERSON> Goh </PERSON> was picked as the next leader by <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> members in 1984, but <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> will remain in power following the Sept. 3 elections and there are no formal plans to end his rule. The dispute and the eventual shift in power has overshadowed the election in the rich island nation, a former British colony that separated from <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> in 1965. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> has been its only prime minister and the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> its only governing party. The <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> said in an editorial today that `` the 1988 election is really about the handing over of the baton from <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuan </PERSON> <PERSON> Yew </PERSON> to <PERSON> Goh </PERSON> <PERSON> Chok </PERSON> <PERSON> Tong </PERSON>, the final passing of power ...'' The governing party captured unopposed 11 of the 81 seats in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> when nominations closed Wednesday. Formal campaigning started today. The party is favored in most of the contested districts against 137 candidates from seven opposition parties and four independent candidates. Only 51 opposition candidates ran in the last election in 1984. All but three seats in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, which was dissolved last week, were held by the governing party, which needs at least 41 to form a new government and run the country for the eighth consecutive term. Opposition leaders have denounced changes in the constitution as attempts to strengthen governing party rule. One proposed constitutional amendment is to change the now ceremonial presidency into an elected office with enhanced powers. It is widely assumed that if the 46-year-old <PERSON> Goh </PERSON> takes power, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, who will be 65 on Sept. 16, will become the first elected president. In that role, he would have veto power over the nation's spending and nominations of <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judges, the attorney general and other senior posts The new president would lack full executive power, but would be able to make speeches in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and have access to all government departments.
