<HEAD>AIDS-Afflicted, Retarded Girl to Stay Home for Present</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A mentally retarded 6-year-old girl afflicted with AIDS may stay in a home instruction program while an appeals court decides whether she must be enclosed in a glass booth if she attends school, a federal judge ruled. <PERSON> Eliana </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> earlier won the right to attend school with other retarded children when the fall term begins Monday in <LOCATION> Hillsborough </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. But she would be isolated in a special 6-by-8-foot booth until she is potty trained and stops sucking her thumb. The child's adoptive mother, <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, fought in court for two years to get her daughter in the class but balked at the glass cage required by District Judge <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Kovachevich </PERSON>. Ms. <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>' attorney, <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanlon </PERSON>, appealed to the 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. He also filed a motion for a local stay, asking that <PERSON> Eliana </PERSON> be allowed to attend classes with no restrictions or be kept in the county's homebound school program until the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> court rules. Chief Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodges </PERSON> ruled on that motion Wednesday, allowing the girl to continue her instruction at home until the appeal is heard. <PERSON> Hanlon </PERSON> said he asked the appeals court for `` expeditious consideration'' that, if granted, could mean a ruling in late September or October. The school board Tuesday displayed the glass booth, equipped with a desk, toilet and sound system, to about 150 parents of other children who will attend the <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exceptional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZAT