<HEAD>With PM-Spy Ring, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Swedish authorities kept three <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc immigrants under surveillance for several years before detaining them this week on suspicion of spying, authorities were quoted as saying today. The suspects _ a married couple and a man _ faced arraignment today on charges of illegal intelligence activity, the Aftonbladet daily said. Swedish radio, however, said the woman was released after questioning and was no longer suspected of criminal activity. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported that the three were among eight people involved in a spy ring that stole defense plans for <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and gave them to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The ring was based in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, while couriers who aided it were based in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, the Times reported. The identities of the suspects were kept secret. Under Swedish regulations, their names may not be published even after they are charged in court. <ORGANIZATION> Aftonbladet </ORGANIZATION> said all three were in their 40s and that one was a physician. They were detained Tuesday morning in the southwestern port city of <LOCATION> Goteborg </LOCATION>, it said. The couple has lived in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> at least 10 years, and the man came to <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> in 1958, the newspaper said. The Goteborgs Posten quoted <PERSON> Torsten </PERSON> <PERSON> Bjorkhede </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Goteborg </LOCATION> head of the security police, as saying the case was handled in cooperation with other intelligence agencies, which he refused to name. `` In any case, it's a question of activity which went on continuously for a long time. It is not a matter of a single incident,'' he said. The surveillance had gone on for `` years,'' he said. Authorities refused to elaborate on the affair. `` This is such a special crime that we can not say much now at the beginning of the investigation,'' Chief Prosecutor <PERSON> Sven-Olof </PERSON> <PERSON> Hakansson </PERSON> was quoted as saying in the <ORGANIZATION> Svenska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dagbladet </ORGANIZATION> newspaper. <PERSON> Hakansson </PERSON> was quoted as saying the suspects could not be arraigned on spying charges since their actions were not directed against <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>. `` Illegal intelligence activity'' is a lesser charge.
