<HEAD>Miners Return to Work After Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 300 employees of a coal mine in southern <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> returned to work today after a 20-hour strike that posed the first worker challenge to the strict economic policies of premier <PERSON> Karoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>. In negotiations with senior government officials, the strikers won a promise the government would try to iron out a quirk in a new income tax law that allows workers on sick leave to earn more than those working regularly. The strikers at the <LOCATION> Komlo </LOCATION> mine 100 miles south of <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> threatened to halt work again if parliament does not remove this quirk. In addition, the government instructed companies to pay bonuses to miners who complained they had lost 30 percent to 50 percent of their bonuses under the new tax laws. The daily <ORGANIZATION> Magyar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nemzet </ORGANIZATION> published the text of a letter sent by the strikers to <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>, who in May became Communist party leader, urging him to settle `` the oft-repeated problems'' of miners at <LOCATION> Komlo </LOCATION>, 100 miles south of <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>. The letter attacked the personal income tax introduced Jan. 1 as part of <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>'s attempts to stimulate the stagnating economy. It said the tax `` does not stimulate increased production or the undertaking of extra shifts.'' `` We all realize the present position and the problems both in the national economy and in our own company, but we are faced with a situation in which our own living conditions have become worse, our real income having been reduced as a result of the inflationary impact,'' the letter added. Inflation has reached 18 percent this year. The income tax has reduced the net income of many workers by introducing taxes on bonuses and earnings from second and third jobs. <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>' government is trying to stimulate the economy to curb a foreign debt of $ 18 billion. The letter justified the strikers' demands for changes in the tax system by noting government and party leaders have said for years that `` they consider the demands of workers legitimate and will see that these are met.'' `` We miners have always honestly done our duty toward the dictates of the national economy, and feel it is the ethical duty of the government to meet our requests now,'' the letter said. Reports of strikes in communist <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> are extremely rare, and the relatively swift media coverage of the stoppage at the <PERSON> Komlo </PERSON> mine appeared to reflect the greater openness of the state-run media since <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> became party leader.
