<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Protest,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Striking Municipal Workers Stage Protest March In Soweto</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOWETO, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 3,000 striking municipal workers confronted security forces at City Hall today after one of the largest protest marches in a black township in recent years. Leaders of the march unsuccessfully demanded a meeting with <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>'s black mayor and white town clerk, and police ordered the strikers to disperse. The strikers then marched back to a church three miles away where the march began. Many of the strikers have been fired in the past two weeks. Trucks loaded with black soldiers followed the procession, and army riflemen were deployed atop the city council chambers. A police helicopter buzzed low over some of the workers as they began the return march, and police fired some tear gas. As they approached City Hall, marchers chanted slogans in support of the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> guerrilla movement and unfurled banners denouncing the local government. Protest marches are illegal in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> unless the government gives advance authorization. The strike, which has disrupted trash collection and other services in the township of 2.5 million people, began in late June when <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> officials said they could not raise pay until a widespread rent boycott ended. The strike was suspended briefly, then resumed July 19. <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>, is one of dozens of black townships nationwide affected by a rent boycott that has cost local administrators more than $ 220 million in unpaid rent. The boycott started in a group of townships south of <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> in September 1985 and spread to <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> in June 1986. The boycott was launched to press a variety of political demands, including lifting the national state of emergency, withdrawing security forces from black townships and releasing political prisoners. Authorities have tried several tactics, including evictions, in an attempt to break the boycott. The latest strategy is to sell at auction the homes of boycott participants. Many blacks have low regard for their local officials, who are widely viewed in the townships as collaborating with the white-dominated central government. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
