<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> met today with South African Foreign Minister <PERSON> Pik </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, and the two men said they aired their differences over apartheid without yelling at each other. `` You name the controversial agenda ... we talked about it,'' said <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, D-Ill., who favors <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic sanctions against <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> `` We had a good, frank discussion.'' <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, who unsuccesfully campaigned for the Democratic nomination for the presidency this year, is on a five-day, fact-finding tour of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> is chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Foreign Relations Subcommittee on African Affairs and will play a major role in deliberations on pending legislation to intensify <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sanctions against <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Limited sanctions have been in effect since 1986. `` We never yelled at each other,'' <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said after the meeting in a <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> suburb. `` The senator has put all the difficult questions. But he has given me the opportunity to put my side. That's all I can ask.'' <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> and other South African leaders say they are pursuing gradual race reforms at their own pace and will not be pressured by sanctions. They also say black South Africans stand to suffer the most from any economic hardships caused by sanctions or foreign disinvestment. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services. <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> predicted Wednesday that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would intensify sanctions