<HEAD>Campaign Says Kitty Dukakis Rumor `Beneath Contempt'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede BOSTON</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First 4 grafs new with Dukakis comments today; picks up 2nd
graf pvs, Symms' comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democratic presidential candidate <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> complained today about recent accusations by Republicans against him and his wife, saying the charges are becoming a distraction to the campaign. Speaking at a roundtable discussion with local reporters, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said he and his wife, <PERSON> Kitty </PERSON>, are having to `` deny nonexistent facts.'' `` I think there's a pattern here,'' he said, raising his hand above his head. `` I hope to keep a high place.'' On Wednesday, the Democrat's campaign issued a statement saying that a suggestion by <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> Republican Sen. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Symms </PERSON> that Mrs. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had burned an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flag is `` totally false and beneath contempt.'' <PERSON> Symms </PERSON>' comment was the third time in a few days that prominent Republicans have aired allegations that the Democrats have rebutted swiftly. The allegations come at a time when Republicans are struggling to shift the campaign focus away from <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> vice presidential nominee <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> and questions about his Vietnam-era service in the National Guard. In an interview Tuesday with a radio station in <LOCATION> Blackfoot </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Symms </PERSON> raised the allegation that Mrs. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> burned the flag during an anti-war demonstration in the 1960s. `` As I've been told, I have n't seen this, but I heard that there are pictures around that will surface before the elections are over of Mrs. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> burning the American flag while she was an anti-war demonstrator during the'60s,'' <PERSON> Symms </PERSON> said. But <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Costello </PERSON>, an aide to Mrs. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, issued a denial Wednesday that read: `` Senator <PERSON> Symms </PERSON>' statement about Mrs. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is totally false and beneath contempt. Mrs. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> believes that the American flag is a symbol of our nation's commitment to freedom and she respects everything for which it stands.'' The suggestion that Mrs. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had burned a flag was `` absolutely false,'' Costello said, adding that while she opposed the Vietnam War, she could not recall ever participating in anti-war protests. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> aides twice called back to heap abuse on <PERSON> Symms </PERSON>. `` I guess the Republicans are doing the limbo to see how low they can go,'' Costello said. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> aide <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Gearan </PERSON> added, `` Senator <PERSON> Symms </PERSON> should be especially careful with rumors.'' The other incidents: _ On Sunday, in an appearance on <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` This Week with <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Brinkley </PERSON>,'' <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> Gov <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> referred to a `` report I saw in the press'' that allegedly said <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> vice presidential candidate <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> had run `` to get his son'' admitted to a special slot in a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> unit. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s son denied the allegation and said he enlisted in the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> in 1968 after personally contacting the commander of the unit he wanted to join. `` He was wrong, absolutely, categorically wrong,'' <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>'s comment. _ On Monday, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON>, the senior Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, called reporters to talk about <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' draft deferments `` I just want to point out that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> received his first of three educational deferments eight months before the Korean War ended,'' <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` My point is not to point fingers at <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, because what he did was legal. But he avoided combat by using his education deferments. There's nothing wrong with what he did because it was allowed. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> swiftly denied any suggestion that he had used college deferments to avoid combat in the Korean War, saying, `` I served my country proudly.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> attended <ORGANIZATION> Swarthmore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> from 1951-1955, requesting and receiving draft deferments in 1952, 1953 and 1954. He said he went to his draft board with several weeks of school left and asked to be drafted immediately. He spent slightly less than two years in the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, including 16 months as part of a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> contingent assigned to the demilitarized zone in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> after the fighting ended.
