<FIRST>u i PM-BurundiMassacre 2ndLd-Writethru a0554 08-25 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burundi Massacre, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0554,0703</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burundi Refugees Tell Of Ethnic Warfare That Killed At Least 5,000</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to simplify lede. Pickup 3rd pvs, `Nearly
two...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KIRARAMBOBO, Rwanda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soldiers in <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION> shot to death hundreds of Hutu tribesmen and dropped firebombs on villages after Hutus burned and hacked hundreds of rival tribesmen to death, refugees say. The Hutu refugees are pouring into <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION> from neighboring <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION>, where ethnic warfare with the rival <PERSON> Tutsi </PERSON> tribe has killed at least 5,000 people and sent more than 40,000 fleeing for their lives across the border. Nearly two weeks after the flare-up in a centuries-old tribal feud between the majority <PERSON> Hutu </PERSON> and dominant Tutsi, refugees from <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION> are arriving at the rate of 2,000 a day into <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s most densely populated country. `` We're trying to help them, but they are overwhelming us,'' <PERSON> Fredric </PERSON> <PERSON> Karangwa </PERSON>, governor of this province, said Wednesday. The influx of refugees, all Hutu, began Aug. 15. The refugees say that a day earlier, Hutus turned on Tutsi tribesmen in two northern communes, hacking hundreds to death with machetes and burning others in huts. None of the refugees admitted involvement in the slaughter, and it was not known what prompted the massacre. Refugees said the Tutsi-dominated army, sent north as peacemakers, turned into executioners when they arrived and found the carnage against their brethren. `` The soldiers were rounding up Hutus and shooting them,'' refugees said. `` They are collecting them into groups, taking them inside houses, closing the doors and windows and then shooting.'' The <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION> government denied the allegations and blamed the bloodshed on exiled Hutus who infiltrated the tiny central African nation. But many of the refugees in <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION> have knife slashes, bullet or shrapnel wounds and burns. The refugees, most of them peasant farmers, said government helicopters dropped firebombs on fleeing villagers. The short, stocky <PERSON> Hutu </PERSON> account for 84 percent of <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION>'s 5 million people, but the tall, lanky Tutsi _ about 15 percent of the population _ control the military and the government. About 8,000 people were crammed into three camps in this section of southern <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION>. Most were camped on hills overlooking a marshland and the <LOCATION> Akanyaru </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, the route to safety for fleeing Burundians. In a local clinic, a doctor and several nurses said they treated dozens of bayonet and bullet wounds. In one crowded waiting room, <PERSON> Reverin </PERSON> <PERSON> Ndururutse </PERSON>, 32, held his 5-year-old nephew, <LOCATION> Immaculata </LOCATION>. The boy's right side was peppered with shrapnel. A bandage covered a finger on his right hand, where the tip had been torn away by a bullet. <PERSON> Ndururutse </PERSON> said his nephew and his own 3-year-old son were the only survivors of a family of 15 herded into a house by soldiers who opened fire. The adults threw themselves on top of the two children, <PERSON> Ndururutse </PERSON> said. Thousands of Burundians have used dugout canoes to cross the slow-moving <LOCATION> Akanyaru </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. They hid in papyrus reeds near the river until dusk and then crossed during the night. Beyond the marshes on the <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION> side, <LOCATION> Rwandan </LOCATION> officials say, the <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION> military has closed the border and set up machine-gun posts to stop the exodus. The site of most of the killing is in <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION>'s remote north around the farming communes of <LOCATION> Ntega </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Marangara </PERSON>. The army has sealed off the areas. But the refugees keep coming and the influx has put a strain on <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION>, which already is hard pressed to deal with its own population of 6.1 million. <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION> has appealed for international aid. A team from the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> High Commissioner for Refugees, which said 41,000 refugees had arrived by Wednesday, is assessing the needs. <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION>, former Belgian colonies, each are about the size of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>. The current bloodletting was the first reported ethnic violence since Maj. <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Buyoya </PERSON> seized power in <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION> in a bloodless coup Sept. 3, 1987 while former President <PERSON> Jean-Baptiste </PERSON> <PERSON> Bagaza </PERSON> was out of the country. After an abortive 1972 coup attempt by Hutus, Tutsis massacred 100,000 Hutus, including most of the tribe's intelligentsia, human rights groups said.
</TEXT>
