<HEAD>Veteran's Medals Arrive In Mail 32 Years Late</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Hume </PERSON> did n't receive his World War II medals or discharge papers by 1955, he decided it was n't `` worth all the hassle.'' But 15 days ago he got a surprise _ a package from the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> that contained his <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campaign </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Asiatic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> and Victory medals he earned while in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> for five years. The package also contained an envelope with a copy of his discharge papers that were first mailed in 1956 to a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> base where <PERSON> Hume </PERSON> had been stationed in the late 1940s. `` I was shocked beyond words,'' <PERSON> Hume </PERSON> said Wednesday from his home in <LOCATION> Moores </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, about 30 miles from <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>. `` I knew in my heart I had earned them, and I guess at that time I just did n't think it was worth all the hassle,'' he said. `` I figured I'd go to a surplus store and buy them some day, but I never did.'' The package had been mailed this month from the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liaison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo </LOCATION>. Inside, an envelope postmarked August 1956 had been mailed from the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Personnel </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> to <ORGANIZATION> Eglin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hume </PERSON> had been stationed there while in the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> following his naval career. The address, however, had been crossed out and `` return to sender'' stamped on the envelope. <PERSON> Dina </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liaison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> could confirm only that the package had come from her office, but not why. Nor did she know where the items had been for the past 32 years. `` We do n't send out anything unless there is a request for it,'' Ms. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hume </PERSON>, however, said he's has n't talked to the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> since 1955. That may change. He said he's still waiting for the Purple Heart and a Good Conduct medal from the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>.
