<HEAD>Group Says School Lunches Improving But Contain Too Much Fat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 School lunches are improving but many still contain too much fat _ at least partly because the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is ignoring its own dietary recommendations, a nutrition group said today. The school lunch program `` is run more as an agriculture support program rather than as a nutrition program,'' said <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Haas </PERSON>, executive director of <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION>. She said the department issued dietary guidelines in 1980 but has done little to see that they are followed in the $ 3.7 billion national school lunch program serving some 27 million children. Many of the foods provided to schools under the commodity purchase program compound the problem because they are high in fat, <PERSON> Haas </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> released a list of traditional menus heavy on fried food, mashed potatoes and sweet deserts and compared that to some school districts that are serving `` healthfully modified'' menus that include baked chicken breasts, raw vegetables, fresh fruit, lowfat milk and salad dressings, and homemade, whole wheat baked goods. Singled out for particular praise was the <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> school district's main course of baked potato topped with chili _ a healthful variation on the chili-topped hot dog favored by other districts. <PERSON> Haas </PERSON> said `` we just do n't buy'' the idea that kids wo n't eat healthy foods and said the trick is to teach them good eating habits when they're in the lower grades, without access to fast food at lunchtime. `` Our young children are a captive audience. We have an opportunity here,'' she said. `` We're trying to build healthy eating behavior.'' The department `` firmly supports the idea that school lunches should be consistent'' with the dietary guidelines, said <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Suzanne </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, deputy assistant secretary for food and consumer services `` However, scientific evidence does not support setting absolute daily intake levels of sugar, fat or sodium for children,'' she said in a statement. `` Nutrition strategies warranted for the general adult population may actually be harmful to children, particularly low-income children, during periods of growth and development.'' She said `` arbitrary decisions to reduce fat may significantly reduce calorie content. Diets very low in fat must be compensated with large amounts of carbohydrate often requiring more food than a child can eat.'' Public Voice made a number of recommendations, among them: _ The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> should set specific limits on the amounts of fat, sodium and sugar permitted in school lunches The department says there is no scientific consensus on such levels for children, but <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> disagrees. _ The department should separate the lunch program from the commodity program and seek out higher-fiber food items for distribution to schools _ The department should establish a national food service management institute to train and help districts serve better quality lunches The department said it has authorized $ 50,000 to study the feasibility of setting up such a program in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>. A report to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is due this fall. _ The department should re-institute a ban on the sale of snack foods on school grounds Currently sales are banned only in cafeterias or during meal periods. The department, citing court cases, says <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would have to pass a specific law if more stringent federal controls are desired.
</TEXT>
