<HEAD>Massachusetts Attorney General, Bush Campaign Debate Pledge Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> did the right thing when he vetoed a `` clearly unconstitutional'' 1977 <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> law imposing criminal penalties on teachers who failed to lead their classes in the Pledge of Allegiance, state Attorney General <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> said today. But <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Steelman </PERSON>, domestic policy director for <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s Republican presidential campaign, said, `` Criminal penalties are not the issue What's at issue here was leadership.'' <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON>, a supporter of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' Democratic presidential bid, said on <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Good Morning America'' that the legislation required criminal penalties against teachers who refused to lead their classes in the pledge, `` even if their own religious convictions said they should n't do that.'' In vetoing the bill, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> obeyed an advisory opinion from the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> that the legislation was unconstitutional. The state's governors have been given about 25 advisory opinions by the high court on legislation in recent years, <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> said. `` Never once, with all those different governors, has any governor signed into law in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> a bill which our state's highest court said was unconstitutional,'' he said `` Since he took an oath of office to uphold the Constitution, he had an opinion from our state's highest court that that law was unconstitutional and he did the only thing that he could do under the circumstances,'' <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. On the same program, <PERSON> Steelman </PERSON> said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was not bound by the court's advice. `` If he wanted to test this issue all he had to do was sign the bill into law and press his case to the national <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. `` What's at issue here is leadership, whether you've got a candidate who will stand up for the majority of Americans beliefs, or whether you've got a candidate who wo n't even stand up for his own beliefs.'' The veto was overriden by the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> and the law went on the books, but it has never been enforced and its constitutionality has not been challenged. The court said the bill was unconstitutional because the state can not force citizens to take an oath that may controvert their religious beliefs.
