<HEAD>Cabinet Minister: Mandela May Be Moved From Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Jailed black leader <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> may be moved soon from the hospital where he has been treated for tuberculosis, a <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> minister indicated today. Information Minister <PERSON> Stoffel </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Merwe </PERSON> declined to say whether <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> would go back to <LOCATION> Pollsmoor </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Prison </LOCATION>, where he has been serving a life sentence for plotting an anti-government sabotage campaign. The <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> leader, jailed since 1962, was moved from <LOCATION> Pollsmoor </LOCATION> to nearby <LOCATION> Tygerberg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> on Aug. 12. Doctors say he is expected to recover fully after a recuperation period of about five months. `` Hospitals are for people that are in need of immediate treatment,'' <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Merwe </PERSON> said. `` If he is not in need of immediate treatment, then it becomes logical to move him somewhere else. Whether inside <LOCATION> Pollsmoor </LOCATION> or outside <LOCATION> Pollsmoor </LOCATION> is another question.'' Asked if <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> was still in need of immediate care, <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Merwe </PERSON> replied: `` Not as immediate as before.'' The government has said it is seriously considering the possibility of freeing <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>, whom many blacks consider their leader. Some officials have suggested that <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>, after he is discharged from <LOCATION> Tygerberg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, would be moved to a private clinic and kept there under custody while the government continues to assess the consequences of his possible relesase. About 60 black women from an anti-apartheid organization came to <LOCATION> Tygerberg </LOCATION> today with flowers for <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>. They left the flowers at a reception desk, then left the hospital dancing and chanting pro-Mandela slogans. The <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is the major guerrilla group fighting the white-dominated government and its system of apartheid. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
