<FIRST>r i PM-Canada-PCBFire     08-25 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Canada-PCB Fire,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Evacuated Residents Spend Second Day Away From Homes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 3,000 evacuated residents spent a second day away from their homes today awaiting the results of soil and water tests to see whether a PCB fire caused long-term contamination of their community. `` We do n't know if we and our homes have been contaminated,'' said <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Charbonneau </PERSON>, one of 150 frustrated evacuees from suburban <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basile-le-Grand </LOCATION> being sheltered in a local school. `` My wife is pregnant. What tells us that her pregnancy wo n't be affected?'' The first test results were to be made public later today, but there was no guarantee the residents would be allowed back into their homes. Most were staying with friends and relatives. The fire burned overnight Tuesday at a depot storing 23,400 gallons of oil tainted with PCBs, or polychlorinated biphenyls. The flames sent a toxic black cloud over a 5.5 square mile area. No one was seriously injured but at least 50 were treated for lung and skin irritation. Quebec Agriculture Minister <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Page </PERSON> estimated that 400 cows could have been contaminated, as well as hundreds of acres of farmland. Authorities sealed off the normally tranquil suburb, 15 miles east of <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>, and told residents not to eat fruit or vegetables from their gardens, drink tap water or use backyard pools until tests were completed. PCBs are suspected of causing cancer and production of the chemical is banned. But supplies formerly used to cool hydroelectric transformers are stored at depots throughout the province, which has no facility capable of neutralizing or destroying the chemicals. Some of the 3,000 residents who were whisked from their homes hired a lawyer on Wednesday to give legal clout to their anger over the presence of potentially deadly chemicals in their neighborhood. `` Clearly, they're looking at a terribly serious type of damage from the health, economic, commercial ... points of view,'' said <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> lawyer <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Liebman </PERSON>. Dr. <PERSON> Gaetan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carrier </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> De </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maisonneuve-Rosemont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> said exposure to PCBs could cause cancers, liver disorders, skin rashes, birth defects and spontaneous abortions. Quebec Premier <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON> and Environment Minister <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON> <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> flew to <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Basile </PERSON> on Wednesday to face hostile residents who have lobbied for years to have the <ORGANIZATION> PCB </ORGANIZATION> dump removed. <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON> said the incident was `` serious but not dramatic,'' and promised compensation to the victims. But residents were not mollified. `` Get that damned stuff out of here,'' shouted <PERSON> Charbonneau </PERSON> to cheers and applause from the crowd. `` You have turned our town into the garbage can of the province.'' Quebec Fire Commissioner <PERSON> Cyrille </PERSON> <PERSON> Delage </PERSON>, directing an inquiry into the fire, said the warehouse's fire and burglar alarm did n't work But he said the depot's owner, <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, had conformed with safety regulations introduced by his department in 1985 for storing PCBs. Residents have charged, however, that the lack of a fence, sprinkler system and security guard made the site a time bomb. <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> said he intends `` to go after'' the company, whose major shareholder is former <ORGANIZATION> Environment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION> employee <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Levy </PERSON>. No cause of the fire has been determined but officials were considering the possibility of arson because of the manner in which the warehouse exploded and blazed. Only about 5,720 gallons of the PCB-contaminated oil burned, leaving the problem of how to dispose of the remainder, officials said.
