<HEAD>Aborigines Demand Return Of Ancestral Land</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 1,500 Taiwanese aborigines marched Thursday to demand that the government return their ancestral lands. The demonstrators, some in aboriginal costumes and wearing yellow headbands that proclaimed `` Return my land,'' ended their march at the office of the Executive Yuan, or cabinet, where they presented a petition. It urged the government to expand aboriginal land reservations and pass a law to protect them. <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> has 10 aborigine tribes who account for 1.6 percent of this island's 20 million people. The demonstrators say many of them have to pay rent to live on ancestral land occupied by the state-run <ORGANIZATION> Taiwan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, or administered by the government's <ORGANIZATION> Forestry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said about 593,000 acres of land have been reserved for aborigines. The demonstrators said their ancestors had 8 million acres in the 1940s when <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> ruled <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>. `` The land policy does not make sense,'' said <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> <PERSON> Wen-hsiung </PERSON>, a leader of the demonstration, `` Why should I rent or buy from the government land that my family has lived on for generations?''
