<HEAD>More Flooding Expected From Tropical Depression That Killed Three</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A tropical depression blamed for three deaths in <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> began moving over the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> today with more flooding expected, forecasters said. The depression was centered about 35 miles west-southwest of <LOCATION> Santo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Domingo </LOCATION> and was packing winds of 35 mph with storm-force gusts, according to a 6 a.m. EDT advisory by the National Hurricane Center in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. `` The movement over land is the only thing that's keeping this from strengthening into a tropical storm,'' said forecaster <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Case </PERSON>. The depression, moving toward the west-northwest at 15 mph, was expected to trigger rainfall totals of 5 to 10 inches in the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>, where flash-flood warnings were in effect. Flash-flood warnings remained in effect for <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, where 6.6 inches of rain were reported over the past 24 hours. Two men and a 12-year-old boy were killed in <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> in two separate incidents Wednesday night when trees crushed their cars as they were driving along rural roads, police said. State Secretary <PERSON> Sila </PERSON> <PERSON> Calderon </PERSON> declared a state of emergency and <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> units were mobilized to rescue families trapped by swollen rivers. In <LOCATION> Mayaguez </LOCATION> on the western side of the island, the <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> ordered hundreds of residents in low-lying areas to abandon their homes. More than 100 homes in different parts of the island were destroyed or seriously damaged by flooding, according to the Civil Defense. Education Department Secretary <PERSON