<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 1233EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Orphans     08-25 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Orphans,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Take First Step Toward Foster Care Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN GILMOUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has taken the first step toward a paid foster care program, changing a system that for years has relied on orphanages as the only official means of supporting children without parents. The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper Pravda reported Thursday on a decree from the Council of Ministers tht laid the groundwork for a foster program, but was vague on its details. Pravda said that under the program, foster parents would be recruited to move into newly constructed `` children's towns,'' where they would be responsible for the rearing of up to 10 children. `` In such children's settlements, apartment houses, a school, a sports center and gardens should be included. Such settlements will be built with local climatic and social conditions taken into consideration,'' Pravda said. But the article did not say how much foster parents would be compensated, give guidelines on who would be considered a foster parent or under what circumstances the person would qualify for financial support. Over the years, some Soviets voluntarily have taken parentless children into their homes, but have received no compensation from the state. If support was forthcoming, it usually was in the form of an offer of food rationing coupons from the Soviet Children's Fund, a charitable organization that was formed only recently. The decree said foster parents should be given priority consideration in booking state-provided vacation lodging and will remain at full pension, if they are elderly or retired. `` Foster parents have to be supported by their respective offices and organizations, they have to be given places at rest houses and santoriums,'' the article said. For years, public discussions on parentless children centered on those who were orphaned. But lately the official media has acknowledged that some children are homeless because of abusive or alcoholic parents, or an unwed mother unwilling to bear the stigma or responsiblity of single parenthood. Officials said three years ago that 300,000 children were being reared in state orphanages and most were placed there by single mothers. In recent years, the media has published reports detailing corruption in some orphanages, where children's food is sold on the black market and they are improperly clothed and housed. The Council of Ministers said authorities will build 30 children's towns, which appear similar in concept to cluster homes in the West, and 150 to 200 children will be housed there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
