<SECOND>AM-Reagan-Library,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Ronald Reagan Library Starts to Take Root</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will have been out of office for over two years _ and 80 years old _ when a library housing his papers and recalling his time in office opens on a cactus-covered hillside northwest of here, if all goes according to plan. Officials originally hoped to make it the first presidential library to open while the president it honors was still in office, but those intentions were scuttled by years of controversy and delay. Nonetheless, plans are moving now. The city council of <LOCATION> Simi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, which must provide water and sewer service to the site on a cactus-covered hillside northwest of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, gave its approval this week. `` Everything is chugging along pretty nicely,'' said <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Rock </PERSON>, a city council member. `` It looks like we're going to go ahead on it.'' <LOCATION> Ventura </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, which must grant a conditional use permit for construction, will hold an environmental hearing Aug. 31. `` We do n't anticipate or see any snail darter incident, although anything can happen,'' said <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Morehouse </PERSON>, a staff planner for the <LOCATION> Ventura </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> government. The library will be reached by a winding road that will rise from an altitude of about 920 feet to 1,190 feet above sea level. The site commands a spectacular view of the countryside and, on a clear day, the peaks of the offshore <LOCATION> Channel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> in the distance. It will be the ninth presidential library in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archives </ORGANIZATION> system and the first west of the <LOCATION> Rockies </LOCATION>. The others are for <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON> at <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Branch </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> at <LOCATION> Hyde </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> in Independence, <LOCATION> Mo </LOCATION>.; <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> at <LOCATION> Abilene </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Ann </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arbor </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. Officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Ronald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reagan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Presidential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> are aiming at breaking ground this fall, possibly in September. Opening date is tentatively scheduled for 1991. Plans to have <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s presidential library open while he was still in the White House were snagged in a controversy over the site. Efforts to locate the library on the campus of <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Palo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alto </LOCATION> fell through in April 1987 ran into stiff opposition from faculty and city landowners. Fund-raising also did not go as rapidly as hoped, and not all of the currently estimated cost of $ 45 million has been raised. Officials wo n't say how much they still need. Even in its new location, the project aroused some controversy, particularly since the part of the 100-acre site on which the building will stand lies within a greenbelt maintained by a decade-old, non-binding agreement among the communities of <LOCATION> Simi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Moorpark </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Thousand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oaks </LOCATION>. The real estate development firm of <LOCATION> Blakeley-Swartz </LOCATION>, which donated the land, originally announced plans to build a 300-room hotel and conference center on 540 acres adjacent to the library site. Officials of the three communities told the county they did not want the library `` used as means for further land-use concessions on any property within the greenbelt.'' So plans for the hotel and conference center have been dropped. In addition to the switch to a <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> site, there have been some changes in design. When the library was to be built at <LOCATION> Stanford </LOCATION>, a separate public affairs institute was planned. Now the project has been scaled down to just the library, with some rooms for conferences and work space for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> when he visits. The basic, mission-style building designed by architects <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Stubbins </PERSON> and Associates for the <LOCATION> Stanford </LOCATION> site has been retained for the new location. An arched colonnade that had been designed to harmonize with other <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> buildings was dropped in favor of straight columns and wooden beams more typical of mission architecture.
