<SECOND>AM-Spy Satellite,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dutch Call For Joint European Spy Satellite</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND DE LIGNY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Western European nations must be prepared to participate in a joint spy satellite program because of increasing work load of American spacecraft, an advisory report said Thursday. The confidential report by a group of Dutch defense experts was presented to Defense Minister <PERSON> Willem </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Eekelen </PERSON> and Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> den </PERSON> <PERSON> Broek </PERSON>. Its main recommendation reflects the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>' increasing efforts to bolster military cooperation in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, along with the region's economic cooperation. A major result of such cooperation would be a closer involvement of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in the defense of <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Although <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> is a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>, it does not take part in <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s integrated military command `` A truly joint spy satellite program would be important for a number of reasons, and the strengthening of the European pillar within <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> would be one of them,'' a source within the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>' defense establishment told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in a Thursday interview. He spoke in exchange for anonymity. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> are developing the Helios espionage satellite, which costs more than $ 1 billion and is scheduled to be launched in 1992. `` It's far too late -LRB- for other European <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> member nations -RRB- to get a foot in the door of the Helios project'' that began in 1986, said the Dutch source, who is familiar with the contents of the advisory report. The report recommended the Dutch government participate in <LOCATION> Helios </LOCATION>' successor, believed to become operational somewhere in the first decade of the next century, according to the source. At present, the Dutch armed forces, as well as those of most other allies, are dependent on those <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> satellite photos that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government allows to be dissiminated, the source said. `` But we forecast that the work load of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> spy satellites will increase sharply in the coming years, what with the verification work emanating from the INF treaty, and in the near future possibly a START agreement,'' said the source. He was referring to the recently-ratified <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate-Range </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> treaty between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, which eliminates all medium - and shorter-range nuclear missiles In <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, the superpowers are currently engaged in negotiations on sharp reductions in their strategic nuclear arsenals, talks known under their acronym START. `` It would be a good thing if the <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> allies were not too dependent on the Americans in their intelligence-gathering from space, and launched their joint satellite in the future,'' the source said. `` And we're especially looking at <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> for such cooperation'' because the French lead in space expertise, according to the source. The report's recommendations, which have not yet been adopted as official government policy, marked another step on the long road toward closer European military cooperation, a concept strongly favored by the Dutch. Last year, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> lobbied for the formation of a Western European naval presence in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, arguing that <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> has a vital interest in keeping open the area's oil shipping lanes. At the time, the Dutch were chairing the <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, an informal, seven-nation defense forum including <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. The efforts led to the dispatch of a joint Dutch-Belgian mine-sweeping force, which operated under the umbrella of British warships in the gulf.
