<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Redevelopment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> board gave initial approval to the largest redevelopment plan in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> history, an ambitious refurbishing of homes and businesses in the blighted <LOCATION> Watts </LOCATION> area. The plan approved Wednesday proposes to redevelop more than 1,900 acres of decaying homes, apartments, small businesses, industrial sites and public housing projects. Also envisioned are new factories on abandoned sites, additional housing, a vocational school and shops and restaurants near the historic Watts Towers by the end of the century. The <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> community of Watts once flourished with tire and auto plants and other factories. But it was ravaged after the 1965 black protests that resulted in riots and fires. Although there are nice homes and small businesses in <LOCATION> Watts </LOCATION>, it is dominated by vacant lots, boarded-up stores, overcrowded slum apartments and the abandoned factory sites. In the first step of the project, the <ORGANIZATION> CRA </ORGANIZATION> authorized an aerial survey of a 3-square-mile area. `` We see that the time is ripe,'' said Councilwoman <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Milke </PERSON> <PERSON> Flores </PERSON>, who represents most of the area and spearheaded the project. `` All of this will come together to provide some jobs and increase business development in the area.'' `` This is what the promise of redevelopment is about, helping communities in great need,'' added Councilman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON>, who represents part of the area. More than 56,000 people live in the area and 86 percent of them are black and 13 percent Hispanic. Most are poor, with an average income of $ 11,427. Most residents rent their homes and have not