residents; Picks up 5th graf, `The two-story ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DIXON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dozens of townspeople, many wearing `` Peace on Earth'' buttons, turned out today to greet a <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> delegation from <PERSON> Dickson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>, outside President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s boyhood home. `` We are carrying with us warmest greetings from all the residents of Soviet <PERSON> Dickson </PERSON>,'' said visiting Mayor <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kartamyshev </PERSON>, speaking through an interpreter from the porch of the house in this small northern <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> city. `` We are enthusiastic because of your warm attitude and generous attitude towards us.'' <PERSON> Kartamyshev </PERSON> said he sensed a `` general feeling of comradeship.'' Mayor <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> city, who worked to make the weeklong goodwill summit a reality, said, `` It's been a long, difficult road making this connection, but we're glad we made it.'' He also said the Soviets were suffering from jet lag after a missed airline connection in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and their arrival in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> on Wednesday. `` But we're not tired,'' said <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> interpreter <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vishnevsky </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. The delegation then entered the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> home for a private tour. `` It's interesting because he's the president and this is where he spent his childhood,'' <PERSON> Kartamyshev </PERSON> had said earlier. `` We connect <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> with the positive changes in the relations between our countries.'' <PERSON> Vishnevsky </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Dickson-Dixon </LOCATION> summit, beginning today, marks the first time a delegation from a small town in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has travele