<HEAD>Selma Elections Spark Arrests; Results Still Not Certified</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MY2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SELMA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> deadlocked along racial lines on whether to certify the election of Mayor <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Smitherman </PERSON> to a seventh term, with his black challenger claiming the mayor was a `` dictator'' who had stolen the election. Two people were charged with disorderly conduct Wednesday in this town of 27,000 people that is a landmark of the civil rights movement, after the council split 3-3 on whether to accept Tuesday's vote. <PERSON> Smitherman </PERSON>'s main challenger, City Councilman <PERSON> Cleophus </PERSON> <PERSON> Mann </PERSON>, who is seeking to become <LOCATION> Selma </LOCATION>'s first black mayor, said one precinct did not open on time Tuesday and that there were other irregularities. `` You stole it!'' <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> shouted at the meeting. `` We might as well have been in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` We sit around and let a dictator run things.'' Returns showed <PERSON> Smitherman </PERSON> receiving 3,752 votes in Tuesday's three-way, non-partisan election <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> received 2,769 votes; <PERSON> Coy </PERSON> <PERSON> Darby </PERSON>, a white challenger, received 453 votes. If the results are upheld, <PERSON> Smitherman </PERSON> would not face a runoff election, because he received more than 50 percent of the vote. After the meeting, <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> nearly came to blows with city attorney <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Pitts </PERSON>, and one campaign aide and another man were arrested on charges of disorderly conduct. A second council meeting, Wednesday afternoon, was boycotted by the council's three black members. Without a quorum, no action could be taken. `` This is one of the worst incidents I've seen since 1964,'' <PERSON> Smitherman </PERSON> said, referring to the year he first took office as mayor and the year when voting rights demonstrations first brought national attention to the city. `` That's the old civil rights crowd, and they're trying to rehash the'60s,'' <PERSON> Smitherman </PERSON> said. `` This is not a representative of the black citizens of <LOCATION> Selma </LOCATION>. That was a bunch of disruptive goons and they got what they came for.'' On March 7, 1965, several hundred civil rights activists began a 50-mile voting rights march to <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION>. State troopers and sheriff's deputies, acting under orders from Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON>, beat marchers as they tried to cross the Edmund Pettus Bridge. Television film of the beatings shocked the nation. Two weeks later, a second, much larger march left <LOCATION> Selma </LOCATION> with the support of the federal government. The clash also was credited with spurring <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to pass the Voting Rights Act, which removed the poll tax and other legal barriers that had discouraged black voter registration. <PERSON> Smitherman </PERSON> said he planned to file a lawsuit to certify the election results. Arrested after Wednesday's council clash were the Rev. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Swift </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON>, 42, one of <PERSON> Mann </PERSON>'s campaign workers; and <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, 21. <PERSON> Pitts </PERSON> said both men shouted at him and threatened him. <PERSON> Swift </PERSON> was arrested a second time when, released from jail, he returned to City Hall and shouted at the mayor that he was `` still a crook because you had people crooked at the polls.'' Later, a policeman was stationed in front of <PERSON> Smitherman </PERSON>'s office and extra patrols were scheduled for his home.
