 <PERSON> Muhammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON>, the boxer who dubbed himself `` the greatest,'' is receiving blood-cleansing treatments from a doctor he calls the greatest in the world. The 46-year-old former heavyweight champion walked into a hospital waiting room Wednesday throwing jabs in the air minutes after undergoing an eight-hour blood treatment to relieve slurred speech and tremors that have plagued him in recent years. The doctor blames <PERSON> Ali </PERSON>'s condition on household pesticide poisoning and not blows to the head. `` I feel like I can fight -LRB- heavyweight champ <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Tyson </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> said in a hoarse voice slightly above a whisper at <ORGANIZATION> Hilton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Head </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> referred questions to his physician, <PERSON> Rajko </PERSON> <PERSON> Medenica </PERSON>, an immunologist who specializes in cancer and blood disorders. <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> underwent plasmapheresis, during which his plasma was removed and replaced with an artificial product prepared by <PERSON> Medenica </PERSON>. Plasma is the fluid in which other components of the blood circulate in the body. Although <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> has been diagnosed as having parkinsonian syndrome, possibly brought on by blows to the head during his boxing career, <PERSON> Medenica </PERSON> disagrees. Calling it `` The Muhammad Ali Syndrome,'' he blamed household pesticide poisoning, which probably affected him so severely because of his rapid metabolism when he was in peak physical condition. <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> likely will return for treatments every three months or so, <PERSON> Medenica </PERSON> said. `` My goal is to remove the circulating toxins. By the end of the year, he should be much better,'' he said. Although <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> had trouble speaking, he moved with ease and appeared to be in good spirits. <PERS