<HEAD>Parliament in Chaos as Government Presses on With Apartheid Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Members of the anti-apartheid <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> walked out of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday to protest a government manuever aimed at pushing through controversial legislation. One of the bills would strengthen enforcement of the Group Areas Act, which mandates racially segregated residential areas. Another would give authorities more powers to evict black squatters. President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> holds an overwhelming majority in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>'s white chamber and is able to gain support for most legislation from the majority parties in the two smaller chambers, one for Asians and one for people of mixed-race. The two non-white chambers, however, have refused to consider the current bills, insisting instead on total repeal of the Group Areas Act. The black majority is excluded from <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and has no vote in national affairs. The leader of the white chamber, F.W. <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON>, announced Thursday that parliamentary rules would be suspended so the six pending bills could be dealt with solely by the white legislators. Progressive Federal members said the rule change made a farce of the parliamentary process. `` You are doing it to pass laws which are repugnant to the vast majority of people in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>,'' said the party's whip, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Malcomness </PERSON>. `` If you put them to a referendum of all the people of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, they will be massively rejected.'' The far-right <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which favors a strengthening of apartheid laws, joined the <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGAN