<HEAD>City Council Votes to Let Police Arrest People Who Look Like Drug
Dealers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The City Council has voted to let police arrest and search people who look or act like drug dealers _ regardless of whether the people are seen making drug deals. The ordinance, approved Wednesday, also says such loiterers may be fined $ 500 if they are known drug dealers or pass money, packages or written material to passers-by in an area known for drug sales. Civil libertarians questioned the ordinance, which says someone may be arrested who `` loiters in a public place in a manner and under circumstances manifesting the purpose of selling any illegal controlled substance ...'' A known drug dealer is defined as someone who has been convicted of drug charges within the last year. Councilman <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> said he proposed the ordinance at the request of <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Caudell </PERSON>, first assistant police chief. `` This allows uniformed police officers to get actively involved in the war on drugs,'' said police Lt. <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Kowalski </PERSON>. But <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>, president of the <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> chapter of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, said he expected the group to challenge the ordinance because it treads on due process and civil rights. <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> said such an ordinance could be used to harass political activities and could increase tension between police and the city's minority communities Councilwoman <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Ragsdale </PERSON> initially cast the only vote in opposition to the ordinance, saying she feared the rights of innocent people could be trampled. But she later reversed her vote, saying she would seek assurances from Police Chief Mack Vines that the ordinance would not be abused.
