<HEAD>Iran and Iraq Hold First Direct Peace Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with direct talks ended,
indirect talks beginning, U.N. chief may appoint panel to determine
who started gulf war. Pickup 8th graf pvs, ``The Council...'' TRIMS
thereafter to tighten.
^By VICTORIA GRAHAM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The foreign ministers of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> today held the first direct peace talks between their countries since the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war began eight years ago. The talks were mediated by the head of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. Iranian Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON> and his Iraqi counterpart, <PERSON> Tariq </PERSON> <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON>, sat at separate tables facing each other across a spacious room. Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> faced them from a third table. The meeting was suspended after 2 -LCB- hours, <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> told reporters. Afterward, the Iranian and <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> delegations moved to separate rooms and <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials shuttled between the two groups and reported to the secretary-general, who remained in the room where the direct talks were held. `` They are consulting,'' <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> told reporters. `` It is not a bad sign, nor a good sign, it's a normal process of consultation,'' he said when asked by reporters if there was a problem with the talks. `` Please do n't interpret this as a sign that things are going well, or badly. They are going normally.'' Earlier <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> told reporters the talks would continue through Sunday. Western diplomatic sources, meanwhile, said the secretary-general was considering naming a three-man panel to determine which side started the war. The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said one representative could be from <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, one from <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and one from the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION>. The direct talks were held in the Art Deco-style Council Chamber of the Palais de Nations. The two foreign ministers and their aides entered separately from the right and left sides. The ministers did not exchange greetings. Reporters were present briefly and watched the beginning of the session on closed-circuit television. As reporters left, <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON> lighted a cigar. `` Your excellencies, I warmly welcome you,'' <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said in English as he led the meeting. The <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> delegation of 15 was seated to his left and the Iranian delegation of 13 was to his right in a triangular set-up of long, widely separated tables. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief said he hoped `` our discussions would be businesslike, constructive and, indeed, productive.'' The Council Chamber overlooks <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> and is decorated with gold leaf and sepia ink murals of human progress and abolition of war. The peace process was expected to be long and troublesome. The issues are numerous _ from disputed border locations to prisoners of war _ and the bitterness between the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> and the Arab sides runs deep. Since a U.N.-supervised cease-fire began six days ago, both sides have traded charges of truce violations and questioned their adversary's sincerity and will for peace. But no serious fighting has been reported. Earlier today, <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON> met separately with <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>. Both ministers were accompanied by their delegations and ignored questions shouted at them from about 100 reporters pressing against crowd control barriers in the main entrance of the building. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said he expects direct talks between <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to last months, but some diplomats believe the peace process could drag on for years. Arriving in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> today, <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON> said the talks should `` arrive at a just, comprehensive, honorable and durable settlement of all outstanding issues between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> accepted the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> cease-fire resolution July 18 after a string of battlefield defeats. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> had agreed to the resolution shortly after the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> passed it in July 1987. The agenda for the Iran-Iraq talks could include troop withdrawal to international borders, resolution of a border dispute, repatriation of prisoners of war, reparations, freedom of navigation in the disputed <PERSON> Shatt </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Arab </PERSON> waterway and the gulf and other issues. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> also is insisting on the creation of an impartial body to determine which side started the war. It has said that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> must be branded the aggressor if there is to be lasting peace. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> invaded <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in September 1980 after border skirmishes. Any ruling on guilt in the war would affect the question of reparations. Official Iranian assessments have put the cost of war damage at $ 350 billion. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has not given an estimate.
