<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Defense contractor <ORGANIZATION> TRW </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> pleaded guilty today to fraudulently overcharging the government up to $ 11 million for military aircraft and M-1 tank parts and agreed to pay $ 3 million in fines. TRW `` deeply regrets that the events occurred'' and has created programs approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to prevent them from happening again, said <ORGANIZATION> TRW </ORGANIZATION> Vice President <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON>, who entered the plea on three counts on behalf of the company, said <ORGANIZATION> TRW </ORGANIZATION> has paid a separate $ 3 million to be applied as an advance payment on restitution to the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The amount of restitution <ORGANIZATION> TRW </ORGANIZATION> owes is to be decided in a pending civil case. The company estimated that it inflated costs by $ 3 million to $ 11 million; government officials have declined to comment on those figures. <ORGANIZATION> TRW </ORGANIZATION> also paid a combined criminal fine and penalty of $ 3 million, one of the largest ever assessed against a defense contractor for procurement fraud, said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>. In connection with the case, two former <ORGANIZATION> TRW </ORGANIZATION> employees have pleaded guilty to defrauding the government, and one former employee faces trial Sept. 6, the government said. <ORGANIZATION> TRW </ORGANIZATION> was charged with conspiring between 1973 and 1984 to falsely inflate labor expenses for the manufacture of aircraft engine parts. A conspiracy to inflate labor costs on compressor fan blades for the M-1 tank took place between 1980 and 1984, <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> said. The third count charges that <ORGANIZATION> TRW </ORGANIZATION> conspired to charge the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for operations and labor that were not performed in connection with the manufacture of blades for the J-79 aircraft engine. `` The three counts ... detail a long-standing course of conduct by <ORGANIZATION> TRW </ORGANIZATION> employees to alter, backdate and destroy documents to conceal the falsely inflated labor costs,'' the government said in a news release. The guilty pleas conclude a federal grand jury investigation that began in 1984, when <ORGANIZATION> TRW </ORGANIZATION> voluntarily disclosed that its employees had engaged in questionable conduct, <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> said.
