<HEAD>Bid Squabble Delays Pizza Delivery To Baltimore Schools</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rival pizza suppliers are fighting, and the result is that school cafeterias will do without for at least five weeks, officials said. `` It's going to cause a riot,'' <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Smackum </PERSON>, director of food service for the <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> school system warned the Board of Estimates on Wednesday. `` Pizza is our most popular item.'' The board voted to toss out bids on 760,000 slices of cheese pizza and re-advertise the contract after spending nearly an hour listening to two vendors argue over whose bid was lower. On a 3-1 vote, the board decided the bidding process made it difficult to determine which of the two bids, $ 219,000 or $ 229,000, was actually the lowest. The dispute arose when <ORGANIZATION> Nardone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> said it would add two-tenths of an ounce of cheese on each slice beyond the 2 ounces required by the contract, thus providing tastier pizza. The extra cheese would be free to the city as long as the federal government continued to provide free cheese through a surplus program, said a spokesman for <PERSON> Nardone </PERSON>. But the rival supplier said the federal program could end this year, raising the cost of the pizza. The start of the school year may be saved for pupils, however. The Board of Estimates approved contracts with suppliers of Mexican-style pizza and French-bread pizza.
