<HEAD>Judge: School Funding Is Unconstitutional</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>'s system of paying for public education is unconstitutional and discriminates against poor urban districts, an administrative law judge ruled Thursday. `` There are unmet educational needs in poor, urban districts and vast program and expenditure disparities between property-rich suburban and property-poor urban school districts,'' Judge <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lefelt </PERSON> said. The ruling comes after nearly two decades of legal and legislative battles, and once again throws into question the way the state funds public schools. It could force the state to spend millions of dollars more each year on education. `` I do not believe that poor urban districts, even with better management practices and the expulsion of politics, could raise sufficient funds ... to address all of the disparities and unmet needs that I believe must be addressed under our constitution,'' <PERSON> Lefelt </PERSON> said. His ruling capped a seven-year legal battle over a lawsuit brought on behalf of 20 school-age children in <LOCATION> Camden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Irvington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. The suit charged that the state funding system leaves poorer districts with far less money than their surburban counterparts and creates disparities in the quality of education. Education Commissioner <PERSON> Saul </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooperman </PERSON> has 45 days in which to accept, modify or reject <PERSON> Lefelt </PERSON>'s ruling. Lawyers for the state and the group that filed the suit, the Newark-based <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, predict the case eventually will go to the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. Although <PERSON> Lefelt </PERSON>'s ruling is a major victory for the law group, the judge did not agree with the group's contention that <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>'s funding system is intentionally discriminatory. Instead, he said, it is `` motivated by cost efficiency and not race.'' <PERSON> Lefelt </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> must revamp the system so poor districts receive more money to improve schools. His decision came more than 15 years after the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> first ruled that <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>'s former system of funding education, with its heavy reliance on property taxes, discriminated against poorer districts. The <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> then enacted a school funding formula, and passed a state income tax in 1976 to pay for it.
