<HEAD>Burundi's Leader Says Soldiers Killed Civilians In Reprisal For
Massacres</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION>'s leader said Thursday his soldiers killed civilians in reprisals for the massacres of rival tribesmen, and he said the death toll from the ethnic war could rise above 5,000. The leader, Maj. <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Buyoya </PERSON>, was quoted on state-run Radio <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION>, monitored in neighboring <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION>. More than 41,000 Burundians have fled to <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION> to escape fighting between the majority <PERSON> Hutu </PERSON> and the minority <PERSON> Tutsi </PERSON>, who control <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION>'s government and military The government said Monday that 5,000 people were killed, but <PERSON> Buyoya </PERSON> said some bodies may not have been counted. The government said its initial figure came from gravediggers sent to bury the dead. <PERSON> Buyoya </PERSON> said the soldiers who killed <PERSON> Hutu </PERSON> civilians were not acting under government orders but started the slaughter after discovering the bodies of Tutsi tribesmen. Many of the Hutu refugees fleeing to <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION> arrived with bayonet, knife and bullet wounds, as well as stories of soldiers killing <PERSON> Hutu </PERSON> on sight. Until Thursday, the <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION> government denied those allegations. The trouble began Aug. 14 when the Hutu attacked Tutsi in two communities in northern <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION>, hacking hundreds to death with machetes and burning people alive in huts, refugees said. <PERSON> Buyoya </PERSON> blamed the trouble on exiled Hutu he said had crossed from <LOCATION> Tanzania </LOCATION>. But refugees blamed most of the deaths on <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION>'s Tutsi-dominated army `` The soldiers were rounding up Hutus and shooting them,'' one refugee said. `` They are collecting them into groups, taking them inside houses, closing the doors and windows and then shooting.'' <PERSON> Reverin </PERSON> <PERSON> Ndururutse </PERSON>, 32, said his 5-year-old nephew and his 3-year-old son were the only survivors of a family of 15 herded into a house by soldiers who opened fire. He said the adults threw themselves on top of the two children. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Hutu </PERSON> civilians, not the army, probably initiated the violence. Spokeswoman <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said, `` It's a tragic situation'' and said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was giving emergency aid to the refugees in <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION> appealed for international aid for the sudden influx of refugees, who still are arriving at an average of 2,000 per day, according to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> High Commissioner for Refugees office in <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION> is the most densely populated nation in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, and the refugees are severely straining the impoverished country's resources <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION> has asked the refugees to return home and promised to help them resettle. In an appeal to diplomatic missions Thursday, <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION> asked for international aid to help rehabilitate the 100,000 people it said were affected by the slaughter. The government said it would need enough tents, blankets, cooking utensils, food and other supplies to aid the affected population for three months, according to a <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> diplomat in <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION>'s capital, <LOCATION> Bujumbura </LOCATION>. `` It just said it had taken stock of what was needed, but did not state amounts,'' said the diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity in a telephone interview. The note did not explain how the government arrived at the 100,000 figure or the three-month time frame, said the diplomat. <PERSON> Buyoya </PERSON> said Wednesday his government was trying to restore order and promised that those found guilty of involvement in the slaughter would be punished, <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burundi </ORGANIZATION> reported in a broadcast monitored in <LOCATION> Nairobi </LOCATION>. He appealed to those who lost their relatives `` to refrain from acts of violence and revenge. Such behavior may reverse our aim of forging ahead in developing <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Buyoya </PERSON>, who seized power in a bloodless coup Sept. 3, 1987, said the victims of the fighting `` belonged to all tribes,'' according to the broadcast. <PERSON> Buyoya </PERSON> said his government would try as soon as possible to lift a 7 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew. The government also has restricted travel between towns and banned meetings of more than five people. <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION>, former <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> colonies, each are about the size of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>. About 6.1 million people are crammed into <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION>, while 5 million live in <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s second most densely populated country. The short, stocky <PERSON> Hutu </PERSON> comprise about 84 percent of the population in both nations and the tall, lanky Tutsi 15 percent. But the Hutu have ruled in <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION> since 1959, when they overthrew the former Tutsi-dominated government and killed an estimated 100,000 people. In <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION>, the Tutsi have held onto power. The most serious threat to Tutsi rule was in 1972, when the <PERSON> Hutu </PERSON> attempted a coup, killing hundreds of Tutsi before the rebellion was crushed. The government retaliated by slaughtering between 100,000 and 300,000 Hutu, incuding most of the tribe's intelligentsia, according to human rights groups.
