<HEAD>Cheering Crowd Greets Soviet Delegation In Dixon</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DIXON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Applause, hearty handshakes and declarations of friendship and world peace greeted a small delegation from <PERSON> Dickson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>, on Thursday on the first visit by Soviet citizens to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s boyhood home. Autograph seekers and well-wishers crowded the yard around the two-story, white frame house where <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> `` Dutch'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> lived in 1920 as a 9-year-old boy with his parents, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nelle </PERSON>, and older brother <PERSON> Neil </PERSON>. A private tour of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> home topped the agenda for <PERSON> Dickson </PERSON> Mayor <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kartamyshev </PERSON>, journalist <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ivanov </PERSON> and interpreter <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vishnevsky </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. `` I have written in the special -LRB- guest -RRB- book inside that a great man deserved a great memory and I am happy to be at such a special place,'' <PERSON> Kartamyshev </PERSON> said as the delegation finished its tour of the three-bedroom house. `` There are a lot of great men who have come from small and ordinary places,'' he said. Mayor <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> of the host city doffed his straw top hat and officially welcomed the Soviet group. `` They are trying to show us that they are good people and they want peace,'' <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> said. `` I hope they will go back knowing we are their friends.'' <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> said the Soviet visitors were suffering from jet lag, having arrived in this town of 15,700 aobut 100 miles west of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, late Wednesday night. But they appeared enthusiastic when greeted by a crowd of about 100. `` We are carrying with us warmest greetings from all the residents of <PERSON> Dickson </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Kartamyshev </PERSON> said. `` Now we can say something has been achieved with our sister-city ties.'' Many in the crowd wore buttons proclaiming `` Peace on Earth'' in English and Russian. Others had pictures of the flags of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. As the Soviets made their way from their tour car to the house, they were stopped several times by onlookers who shook their hands, slapped their backs and welcomed them. A local radio station broadcast the ceremonies live, including a 15-minute speech by <PERSON> Kartamyshev </PERSON>, who also answered questions from reporters. `` We associate <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> with the positive changes in relations between our countries,'' <PERSON> Kartamyshev </PERSON> said. `` It's interesting to see where he spent his childhood.'' The Soviet mayor said he hoped the spirit of `` glasnost,'' a new spirit of openness in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> society, would allow a reciprocal visit by <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON>'s mayor and other Americans to his town. It is a remote, frontier village of about 5,000 in extreme northern <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>, above the <LOCATION> Arctic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Circle </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dickson </PERSON>, named for <PERSON> Oskar </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickson </PERSON>, a 19th-century Swedish merchant who provided supplies for expeditions for early Arctic explorers, generally is closed to foreign visitors because of nearby military installations. <PERSON> Kartamyshev </PERSON> said he no longer fears a world war between the superpowers because of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s recent peace initiatives and said the Dickson-to-Dixon good-will summit was evidence of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> president's success. The Soviets brought gifts for their hosts, including a medallion inscribed `` From Dickson With Love'' and bearing the American and Soviet flags united in a heart-shape. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, son of a shoe salesman and a dressmaker, lived in <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> from 1920 until he left for college in 1928. However, his parents never owned a house and lived in several places during the 17 years they called <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> home. The house picked as the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> museum was the first place the family lived in <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> and it's the home <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said he remembered best. The Soviets where shown the bed <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> shared with his brother, the wallpaper in the living room, decorated just as it was in 1920, and they even saw the loose tile around the fireplace where <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> hid pennies.
