 Two bombs exploded Thursday outside banks, causing damage but no injuries, a government official said. Police suspect the Catalonian separatist group <ORGANIZATION> Terra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lliure </ORGANIZATION>. The Basque separatist group <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, claimed responsibility for an Aug. 21 car bomb that killed two civil guards in the northern town of <LOCATION> Estella </LOCATION>. A <ORGANIZATION> Barcelona </ORGANIZATION> civil governor's office spokesman said the first bomb exploded at 3:10 a.m. in the doorway of a <ORGANIZATION> Banco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Espanol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credito </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Banesto </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- branch office in the suburb of Hospitalet de Llobregat. The blast damaged the building and four nearby cars in the northeastern city, the official said. Less than two hours later, an explosion rocked a downtown Banco Central office and shattered glass in surrounding buildings, he said. The official said no group claimed the attacks, but the two bombs were of a type used by <ORGANIZATION> Terra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lliure </ORGANIZATION>, which seeks independence for <LOCATION> Catalonia </LOCATION> and has carried out frequent attacks in <LOCATION> Barcelona </LOCATION>, capital of the autonomous region. In the Basque country, <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION> claimed responsibility for the Aug. 21 car bomb that exploded as two civil guards drove by in their patrol car, killing them instantly and slightly injuring a woman and her young child in a nearby apartment. In notes to several Basque newspapers and radio stations, <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION> rejected the government's condition that the group lay down its weapons before beginning negotiations to end separatist attacks. The government also has said it will not talk to <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION> until the group releases businessman <PERSON> Emiliano </PERSON> <PERSON> Revilla </PERSON>, who was kidnapped outside his <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> home six months ago. <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION>, whose name stands for Homeland and <ORGANIZATION> Liberty </ORGANIZATION> in the Basque language, seeks independence for the three-province Basque region and <LOCATION> Navarre </LOCATION>, the neighboring region where the attack took place. <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION> has claimed responsibility for killing more than 600 people, mostly civil guard, military and police officers, since taking up arms in 1968. It has killed eight people this year.
