<SECOND>AM-Chile-Analysis,0764</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chile Moves Toward Legitimizing Presidential Plebiscite; Doubts
Persist</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Military President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s decision to lift all states of emergency helps meet opposition conditions for fair play in an October presidential referendum But other measures being urged by critics have yet to be adopted, and the critics say doubts persist that the vote will enjoy legitimacy. `` We still have to wait and see,'' <PERSON> Patrico </PERSON> <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON>, president of the centrist <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, told foreign reporters. Gen. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> on Wednesday signed decrees to end all states of emergency for the first time since he seized power in a 1973 coup. The decrees take effect upon publication in the official bulletin, expected this week. His right-wing government plans a referendum on a single presidential nominee to be picked by military commanders, including <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, at a meeting set for next Tuesday. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, who is also the army commander, is expected to be nominated. No exact date has been announced for the yes-or-no ballot, but <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> said it will be in early October. If a majority vote yes, the nominee will be president until 1997. If most voters reject him, open elections will be held in 1990, with <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> remaining in place until then. Opposition parties and the local <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> set four basic conditions for a fair ballot: high voter registration; an end to the states of emergency; equal access to the mass media, and a vote free of fraud and intimidation. By mid-August more than 7 million of <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s 8 million eligible voters had registered, thus resolving the first condition The second condition was met, at least formally, by Wednesday's decrees Under the emergency states, the right to assembly and freedom of the press could be restricted and the government could jail and expel leftist critics. With the lifting of the measures, opposition groups can stage rallies without government authorization. `` It's impossible to image conducting a campaign without the right to gather publicly,'' <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> said. He said the opposition would wait and see if the government is sincere about its vows to respect civil liberties. <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lagos </PERSON>, a prominent Socialist in a 16-party opposition coalition, said Thursday, `` I'm left with the sensation that this is a cosmetic operation.'' <PERSON> Monica </PERSON> <PERSON> Madariaga </PERSON>, a former justice minister under <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> who now is critical of his government, said the president `` has placed the country under a state of observation'' and could declare a new state of emergency if the opposition failed to behave. On Tuesday, navy commander <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Merino </PERSON> warned that even stronger emergency measures could be adopted if public disturbances occurred. But Roman Catholic Church leaders expressed confidence in the government's good faith. Cardinal <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Fresno </PERSON> said in a written statement that he received news of the measure `` with satisfaction, and asks all Catholics to intensify their prayers for the welfare of the country.'' Still pending is the question of access to television and the press. Television, which is tightly controlled by the state, and the biggest newspapers have provided little space to the opposition. Political groups campaigning for a `` no'' vote complain that their advertisements are rejected but there is intensive pro-government propaganda. `` Under these conditions, the plebiscite loses legitimacy,'' <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION> said in a recent interview. Election laws drawn up by the government guarantee each side 15 minutes of free television time each day in September, from 10:45 p.m. to 11:15 p.m. Opposition leaders say the hour is too late for many people and that this still fails to compensate for hundreds of pro-government ads broadcast and published during the past year. `` There is an immense abuse and fraud by the government in access to television,'' said <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Zaldivar </PERSON>, a Christian Democrat. He said that because of unfair conditions, if the government declares a victory in the ballot `` the immense majority of Chileans are not going to believe it, and the entire world is not going to believe it.'' But he and other opposition leaders virtually discount the possibility of a fraudulent count on the night of the ballot. They said election laws authorizing the presence of independent monitors at polling places will make any attempt at direct fraud too obvious. The opposition coalition, pro-government parties and a church-sponsored group each has established a network of thousands of monitors to provide parallel vote counts.
</TEXT>
