<TEXT>
 Officials declared a state of emergency Thursday at two <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> psychiatric hospitals, saying patients were squeezed into overcrowded rooms and forced to sleep in shifts on cots in hallways. The action allows the state to begin moving patients to less crowded facilities without permission of family or guardians, said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Osborn </PERSON>, a spokesman for state <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Surles </PERSON>. `` There is no patient privacy, no ability to accommodate patients who are not able to be admitted as in-patients right away,'' said the city's mental health chief, Dr. <PERSON> Sara </PERSON> <PERSON> Kellermann </PERSON>, who had urged <PERSON> Surles </PERSON> to declare the emergency. `` As a result they end up eating with trays on their laps, end up sleeping on very rudimentary cots ... and they are literally sleeping in hallways in four-hour shifts,'' she said. Hospital employees would wake patients up after a few hours to allow others to lay down, she said. Though officials were aware of overcrowding at psychiatric facilities in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, they said they did not realize the magnitude of the problem until they conducted an in-person investigation. The city-run <LOCATION> Kings </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> has 160 beds for mental health patients and a current population of 195, according to <PERSON> Osborn </PERSON>. Matters are worse at nighboring <ORGANIZATION> Kingsboro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, where there are 566 beds and 736 patients. <PERSON> Osborn </PERSON> said it was not unusual to see six patients squeezed into a room intended for four. <PERSON> Kellerman