<HEAD>Sudan Struggles With Shortages; Nile Recedes After Floods</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Name Abdelrhman cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Flood-ravaged <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> scraped for such basics as bread, electricity and drinkable water on Thursday. Floodwaters covered about 280 square miles of land in the north, the state-run <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said. Electricity, transportation, communications were badly affected. The Irrigation Ministry reported a slight drop of 1.2 inches in the swollen <LOCATION> Nile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> at this capital city of 4 million people, and forecast a continued decrease over the next few days. Prime Minister <PERSON> Sadek </PERSON> <PERSON> el-Mahdi </PERSON> has warned, however, that the flood situation could deteriorate again in the first week of September, the peak rainy season. The <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said water covered an area stretching from <LOCATION> Merowe </LOCATION>, 200 miles north of <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Abri </LOCATION>, 100 miles south of the Egyptian border. It said islands in the Nile were completely submerged and their inhabitants had been evacuated to safe areas. The Nile overcame levees in several areas in <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>, including one containing many diplomatic residences. Military units were mobilized to help stop the waters' advance. Whole suburbs in <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> were flooded. Streets were turned into impassable mud tracks, hampering relief operations. Torrential rains Aug. 4-5 triggered the worst floods in this northeast African country's history. The floods have left 1.5 million people homeless, at least 91 dead, tens of thousands of homes destroyed and some of <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s most fertile farmland inundated. Worst affected were shantytowns at the outskirts of <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>. The towns, made up of tin, canvas and mud hovels, house between 750,