<SECOND>AM-Lucchese Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0671,0873</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Begins Deliberating In 2-Year Racketeering Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with details from first day of
deliberations, edit, picking up 4th graf pvs, `The trial ....'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal jury Thursday began deliberating the fate of 20 reputed organized crime figures in what is believed to be the nation's longest federal criminal trial. The jury in the 21-month-old trial faced a vast array of materials, including more than 40,000 pages of transcripts, the testimony of 89 witnesses and 850 exhibits. The 12-member panel, which retired for the night and was to return Friday morning, made its first request within 10 minutes of entering the jury room, seeking copies of the indictment and transcripts of opening arguments. Attorneys then began arguing about what portions of the opening arguments should be excised, only to have the jury send out another note two hours later canceling the request. Meanwhile, the indictment question was resolved when it was learned that the jury already had a copy of it _ along with a roomful of exhibits _ but did n't know it was there. The jury must decide 77 separate charges, basing its deliberations on the complex instructions it received Wednesday from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ackerman </PERSON>. The trial has exhausted participants and backed up the federal courts in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. One prosecutor became a father twice. An attorney who had been commuting from <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> died of cancer, touching off a dispute over his replacement that went all the way to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. One witness was on the stand for four months. `` My marriage began and ended during this trial,'' said defense attorney <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Noto </PERSON>. `` The attention that I chose to devote to -LRB- it -RRB- rather than to my new husband had a great deal to do with it.'' `` It's a monster,'' Ms. <PERSON> Noto </PERSON> said. `` It's an amorphous, uncontrollable, confused monster.'' Jury selection began Nov. 20, 1986, when the first of 1,200 people were screened for the panel, and opening arguments began in March 1987. Since then, one defendant briefly attended court in a hospital bed until his moaning interfered. Another passed out. A third, acting as his own attorney and given to telling jokes to the jury, cross-examined his cousin _ who on the stand apologized for once shooting the defendant five times in the head. The case began in August 1985 with the unsealing of a racketeering indictment naming <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> `` Tumac'' Accetturo of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, who authorities say is a captain in the Lucchese crime family, and the other defendants. Accetturo allegedly controlled the powerful <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> faction of the family, which authorities say ran loan-sharking, illegal gambling, drug-dealing and fraudulent credit card operations across the state. The government charges the group operated out of a <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> luncheonette called the Hole-in-the-Wall, where pictures of legendary gangsters <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Capone </PERSON>, <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON> <PERSON> Lansky </PERSON> and <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> `` Lucky'' <PERSON> Luciano </PERSON> hung. Key witnesses, many of whom were criminals and onetime associates of the defendants, testified about the group's reputed mob traditions: kisses of respect and `` tribute'' payments for the boss; `` sit downs,'' meetings held to resolve disputes; and visits to mob hangouts by luxury-hotel manicurists to do the nails of defendants. Defense attorneys said the witnesses, their imaginations fired by movies and television shows, had manufactured the scenes. During a month of summations, they urged the jury to disregard testimony from criminals, confessed liars and drug-users _ many cooperating with the government in exchange for leniency and financial support. That support, the defense says, exceeds $ 300,000 _ just part of the millions of dollars invested in the case by the government. Court-appointed attorneys have received an estimated $ 3 million. Then there are the $ 175,000 paid to jurors; the salaries of three prosecutors, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> case agent, judge, and extra <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> marshals for security; and copying costs for a mountain of documents. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Alito </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who started his job after the trial began, says the expense is worth it, although he acknowledges concerns about the trial's length. `` We will do everything we can to keep -LRB- future -RRB- trials at reasonable lengths,'' he said. According to the Administrative Office of the Courts in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the trial has exceeded what previously was thought the longest federal criminal proceeding, the `` Pizza Connection'' case, which ended in March 1987 after 17 months. The jury convicted 18 men for participating in a heroin ring that used pizzerias as fronts. <PERSON> Ackerman </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> trial has been stressful. `` Because of its length, I've been rationing my strength,'' he said, calling the jury's patience `` absolutely astonishing.'' Two jurors were dismissed and replaced by alternates early in the trial, while a third was excused just last month after she told the judge the trial was `` making me crazy.'' Defense attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> has the unusual problem of handling his client's interests as well as those of the city of <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION>, of which he was elected mayor this spring. `` It has caused a lot of late nights at City Hall,'' he said.
