<HEAD>Human Rights Conference Opens Amid Polish Strikes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KRAKOW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 600 activists from East and West came together for an unofficial human rights conference Thursday, while the government confronted workers striking to legalize Solidarity. Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> was scheduled to give the opening address at the conference, one of the largest ever held in an <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc country. But he sent his apologies, saying he could not come because he was holed up with other strikers at the Lenin shipyard in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>. `` The highest necessity forces me to stay away,'' the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize laureate wrote to conference participants. `` I am taking part in a strike to defend human and workers' rights. `` I believe that the epoch of totalitarian systems based on violations of human rights seems to be coming to an end in this part of the world.'' Also at the conference Thursday, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> congressional staffer <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> announced that the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would soon approve a $ 1 million grant to help Solidarity, which was outlawed by the Polish government in 1982. Solidarity was the first independent labor movement in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc. <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON>, general counsel to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which does research and provides support for Conservative members of the chamber, said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> already has provided two such grants to Solidarity. He called on the Polish government to legalize the trade federation. `` Any improvement in relations between the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and the government of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> must be predicated on an improvement in the human rights situation in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> said. `` I can tell you w