 A high-ranking officer received a letter of reprimand and four other supervisory personnel were given nonpunitive letters of caution in the death of a rescue swimmer trainee, a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said Thursday. The information was disclosed as proceedings began in the court-martial of Lt. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Torchia </PERSON>, former officer in charge of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rescue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Swimmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> where Airman Recruit <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON>, 19, of <LOCATION> Appleton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, died March 2. Testimony at a June investigative hearing indicated <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON> died from a fear-induced heart attack or drowning. Instructors allegedly pushed <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON> back into a swimming pool and held his head under water after he had panicked, climbed out and shouted that he wanted to quit. <PERSON> Torchia </PERSON>'s former boss, now-retired Capt. C.L. <PERSON> Lavinder </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who headed the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Schools </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION> at the time of <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON>'s death there, received a letter of reprimand for dereliction of duty from Rear Adm. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, said Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Hessler </PERSON>, a public affairs officer. <PERSON> Hessler </PERSON> said the letters of caution were issued to an officer and three enlisted men with ranks of chief petty officer or above, but their identities could not be disclosed because the punishment did n't go on their records. <PERSON> Torchia </PERSON> and an enlisted ins