<DATELINE>NEW CARROLLTON, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One person was killed and four others were injured Thursday when a tractor-trailer carrying 8,000 gallons of diesel fuel overturned and exploded on the Capital Beltway during the evening rush hour, fire officials said. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> area traffic was snarled as a two-mile stretch of the Beltway, the highway that forms a loop around the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, was closed for four hours. Traffic in one direction on that section of the highway remained halted later into the evening. The accident occurred when the truck struck a van, lost control and rolled over the highway's center barrier, said Prince <PERSON> George </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> DeStefano </PERSON> Sparks from the skidding truck ignited the fuel as the fuel container broke up in the wreck. The truck's 32-year-old driver was taken to Prince <PERSON> George </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> with burns on 18 percent of his body One person, believed to be male, smashed into the wreckage in a car and was instantly killed, <PERSON> DeStefano </PERSON> said. One man in the van that was struck by the truck suffered spinal injuries and was flown to a shock trauma center in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, <PERSON> DeStefano </PERSON> said. Two other men in the van received minor injuries. Names of the victims had not been released late Thursday. Authorities said the explosion posed no immediate danger to area residents, and let the fire burn out by itself. `` It posed no hazard because the tank had already opened and was burning,'' <PERSON> DeStefano </PERSON> said. `` The best way to dispose of the product is to let it burn.''
