NIZATION> building early Thursday, temporarily paralyzing the 500-member electoral college. The body must finish its work in time to seat a new House by Sept. 1. On that date, both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> are to meet in joint session to hear outgoing President <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Madrid </PERSON>'s state-of-the-union address The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, sitting as a second electoral college, continued hearings normally Thursday to certify the election for its 64-member body. The <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> had not lost a presidential election since it was founded in 1929. But the July 6 balloting marked the first time the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> won the presidency with less than 70 percent of the votes cast. Returns this time gave <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> victory and a single six-year term by 50.36 percent of the vote. <PERSON> Cuauhtemoc </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> leader that broke away to head the leftist <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> coalition </ORGANIZATION>, came in second with 31.1 percent. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clouthier </PERSON> of the conservative <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> came in third with 17 percent. For the first time also, the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> lost its complete domination of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. Four opposition senators already have been certified for their posts. By law, the deputies - and senators-elect sit as separate electoral colleges to certify their own elections, and then the 500-member <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> sits as an electoral college to certify the presid