<HEAD>Memorial Garden for Dorothy Parker Designed to Improve
Black-Jewish Ties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER BRANDLON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The ashes of celebrated writer and wit <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> will be interred in a memorial garden at <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in a gesture of friendship between blacks and Jews, the director of the civil rights organization said Thursday. The dedication of the garden on Sept. 16 will put an end to the homelessness of <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>'s ashes, which have resided for years in a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> office file cabinet. <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, who was Jewish, was an outspoken civil libertarian. When she died in 1967, she left her estate to the Rev. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, and, on his death, to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for the Advancement of Colored People. `` In celebrating Ms. <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, we proudly celebrate our relationship with the Jewish community, reaffirming and renewing our commitment to work hand in hand to erase the stain of all forms of racial, religious, sexual and ethnic injustice and intolerance from our society,'' said <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hooks </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION>. Rabbi <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> <PERSON> Saltzman </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Baltimore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congregation </ORGANIZATION> called the memorial `` a testament of good will toward <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, and, through her, to the Jewish community.'' Hooks offered to have the ashes buried at the organization's national headquarters after learning this spring they were being kept in lawyer <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Dwyer </PERSON>'s office Hooks said most people know little more about <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> than her oft-repeated quip, `` Men seldom make passes at girls who wear glasses.'' `` There was much more to Ms. <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> than those sparse and not totally accurate two lines _ her short stories, her reviews, her essays, her plays, her movie scripts and her conversational gems,'' Hooks said. `` One of my favorites was her reported remark when one of her archrivals was described as her own worst enemy. ` Not while I'm around,' Ms. <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> retorted They do n't make them like that anymore.'' The memorial garden will be located in a tiny grove of towering white pine trees behind the chapel of a former monastery now occupied by the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION>. Its centerpiece will be a plaque on the ground surrounded by a circle of brown brick. Plans call for leaving a natural floor of soft pine needles. The circle represents the Round Table at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Algonquin Hotel, legendary for the gab sessions held there by <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> and a collection of the best-known literary figures of her time, said <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, dean of the <ORGANIZATION> Howard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Architecture </ORGANIZATION> and Planning. The architecture school provided the design and a minority-owned construction company will do the work, <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said. Hooks said he did not know how much the project would cost. The evening before the garden's dedication, a one-woman show about <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>'s life, written by and starring <PERSON> Laurel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ollstein </PERSON>, will premiere at the Arena Playhouse in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>. The play is titled, `` Hope, Laughter and a Sock in the Eye.''
