<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democratic vice presidential candidate <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, a decorated World War II bomber pilot, was booed by veterans on Thursday when he said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and the Democrats could be trusted with the nation's defense. `` The simple truth is this: Gov. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is a veteran, a patriot, and an advocate of American strength and steadiness,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> told the Veterans of Foreign Wars convention in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` He can be trusted as a defender of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> security _ and as a champion of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> values.'' While President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has been a strong advocate for the military, he `` has purchased military strength at the expense of national solvency,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said, warning of the threat of the huge national budget and trade deficits. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> himself was warmly received by the crowd and got a standing ovation. But in trying to make the case for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> on defense, he was interrupted four times by boos or jeers _ once when he mentioned former President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s name. At one point, when <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> talked about <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> `` bringing fiscal responsibility and management competence to our national defense programs,'' the VFW's national commander, <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stock </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, had to stand and quiet the crowd. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> then asked for the `` courtesy to debate,'' and received applause. The booing of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> appeared to be led by the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> delegation to the convention. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, a retired veteran who said he was once the Democratic chairman in <LOCATION> Saugus </LOCATION>, <