<HEAD>Challenger Center `Mission Site' Opens in Houston</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than two and a half years after the Challenger exploded, relatives of the crew turned the astronauts' dream of teaching children about space into reality Thursday with the opening of the first Challenger Center The center at <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION>, paid for with a $ 150,000 private grant, will give students an opportunity to make a simulated space flight complete with a mission control center and scientific experiments. `` We knew we could n't launch a satellite. Discovery will do that for us, but we could continue scientific and education objectives of that mission,'' said <PERSON> June </PERSON> <PERSON> Scobee </PERSON>, widow of Challenger commander <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Scobee </PERSON> and chairman of the board of the Challenger Center. `` The Challenger Center mission began with the Challenger crew. The idea to continue it was a mission by the families,'' she said, accompanied at the opening by relatives of other crew members. `` This is a milestone event,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Barram </PERSON>, vice president of corporate affairs for <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which donated computers to the center. `` The center and its educational innovations are giant steps down new pathways to knowledge for our children _ and for us.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Scobee </PERSON> and the other Challenger relatives conceived the center as a memorial to the deceased crew and their educational mission. The Challenger carried <PERSON> Christa </PERSON> <PERSON> McAuliffe </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Concord </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION>, high school teacher who was to have conducted the first classroom experiments from space. The <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> center is expected to se