refugees from <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guiana </LOCATION>. The refugees have said they will not go home until they have guarantees the fighting will stop. Meanwhile, 14 barefoot gold miners in a dug-out canoe arrived Thursday in a small village in <LOCATION> Brokopondo </LOCATION> province in central <LOCATION> Suriname </LOCATION>, and said nine rebels with machine guns had attacked their isolated camp two days earlier. They said the guerrillas beat them and stole all their valuables. The miners said the rebels took the small amount of gold they had, loading it onto two boats owned by the mine, and made off with their shoes, a refrigerator, cooking utensils and shotguns. The 14 men reached the village after paddling two days down <LOCATION> Sarakreek </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in a large canoe given to them by the rebels, who told them their mining camp was operated by <PERSON> Bouterse </PERSON> and ordered them to abandon it.
