<DATELINE>JASTRZEBIE, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Riot police crushed strikes at two southern coal mines and beat some men after dragging them from the mines, activists said today. Witnesses said strikers at a third colliery escaped underground. Despite the police raids in this coal-rich region where miners nine days ago began <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s most serious strike wave since 1981, activists said strikes continued in the Baltic ports of <LOCATION> Szczecin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Borynia </LOCATION> mine in <LOCATION> Jastrzebie </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Morcinek </LOCATION> mine in nearby <LOCATION> Koszyce </LOCATION> were completely cleared of strikers during the night, according to workers from each of the mines. About 40 miners at the <LOCATION> Moszczenica </LOCATION> mine managed to elude police during the raids and descended into the shaft with bread and lanterns, witnesses said.
