 Sports agents backed by a reputed mobster lured college athletes with lucrative bonuses, then threatened them with violence if they refused to sign contracts, according to an indictment of three agents and a pro football player. The long-simmering scandal tainting college athletics boiled over Wednesday with the indictment of New York-based agents <PERSON> Norby </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON>, 58, and <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloom </PERSON>, 29, on charges of racketeering, mail fraud, wire fraud and extortion. They are accused of using money, gifts and threats to enlist dozens of players into signed _ in some cases postdated _ agreements allowing the agents to represent them in professional contract negotiations. If the players tried to back out of the deals, they were warned that <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bloom </PERSON> had friends who would visit them and break their legs, said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Anton </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Valukas </PERSON>.
