<SECOND>BC-Grocery Express, ADV 28,0705</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 28, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Recovering Company Delivers Convenience to Busy Customers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Supermarkets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX2 of Aug. 23</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The unassuming green building in this city's produce district looks like a warehouse and, like a warehouse, it's filled with row after row of boxes and cans of food. But <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Garvey </PERSON> sees it differently. `` This is a laboratory,'' she says. `` We're creating a new industry.'' <PERSON> Garvey </PERSON>, 31, is president of <ORGANIZATION> Grocery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION>, a company that delivers just about anything you can find on a supermarket shelf to people who ca n't or do n't want to shop and who are glad to pay a little extra for convenience. `` People have less and less time. And that trend is not reversing,'' <PERSON> Garvey </PERSON> said in a recent interview. About 5,000 people in the city and the northern <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> save time by ordering groceries from <PERSON> Garvey </PERSON>'s 7-year-old company and having them delivered for a flat fee of $ 4.25. Prices are about 15 percent higher than at large supermarkets and about the same as at a corner grocery, <PERSON> Garvey </PERSON> said. Forty percent of her patrons are businesses, elderly and homebound people, but the rest are two-income couples, professional singles or families with young children. `` These are people who have no time but lots of demands on their time,'' she said. <PERSON> Katherine </PERSON> <PERSON> Craven </PERSON>, a writer and homemaker, first called Grocery Express 6 -LCB- years ago when she was pregnant and did n't want to climb stairs to her second-floor Victorian flat with bags of groceries. `` For me it's been a great thing, and particularly in the winter or if someone is sick, it's just a godsend,'' said <PERSON> Craven </PERSON>. Customers order from among several hundred items in Grocery Express' catalog, a 128-page guide that includes fresh flowers, restaurant meals and food gift baskets as well as fresh meat and produce and canned and packaged goods. Each item has a number, which <ORGANIZATION> Grocery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION>' clerks punch into a computer, noting whether customers want their chicken boned or bananas barely ripe. Customers also can file orders through their home computers. Orders are put together in the company's 18,000-square-foot warehouse and delivered in one of seven vans. <PERSON> Garvey </PERSON>, who has an economics degree from <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, learned about business from her family's company, <ORGANIZATION> Garvey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Wichita </LOCATION>, Kan.-based concern dealing in oil and gas, grain and real estate. Grocery delivery, while not a new idea, has not been a very profitable one. Over the past 15 years, other entrepreneurs have started companies like <ORGANIZATION> Grocery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> but failed, <PERSON> Garvey </PERSON> said. Grocery Express nearly became one of those failures after an enthusiastic beginning. <PERSON> Garvey </PERSON> was an original investor, but it was her former husband, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Meagher </PERSON>, and friend <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Coghlan </PERSON> who were the real founders, she said. <PERSON> Garvey </PERSON> became more involved in the business and took it over two years later. In 1984, the company's sales had leveled off at about $ 2 million, but the firm had yet to turn a profit. Grocery Express raised its prices, but lost customers and even more money. The next year, it came close to shutting down. But <PERSON> Garvey </PERSON>, who describes herself as eternally optimistic, was sure she could turn the company around. `` I was just certain this is a business people need,'' she said. `` I looked at it from a different point of view _ long term _ and was willing to spend the additional time and money.'' Since 1985, <PERSON> Garvey </PERSON> has put between $ 1.5 million and $ 2 million into the firm, reduced prices and used direct mail and radio ads to regain former customers and win new ones. In 1986, sales rose to $ 2.3 million with a loss of $ 330,000, and last year, sales increased to $ 2.7 million while the company's loss shrank to $ 75,000. <PERSON> Garvey </PERSON> expects to turn a profit this year. She's also planning to expand her delivery area and is considering opening another warehouse. Of her company's future, she said, `` It's going to be interesting to see.''
</TEXT>
