<HEAD>Oil Prices Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil futures prices continue to drift lower in slow summer trading. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, oil futures finished mostly lower for a second straight day Wednesday in light trading. Contracts for October delivery of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Intermediate, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, slipped 2 cents a barrel to close at $ 15.68, after falling 21 cents a barrel on Tuesday. Contracts for September delivery of wholesale unleaded gasoline rose 0.33 cent to finish at 47.51 cents a gallon. Most other contract months for gasoline declined. Wholesale heating oil for September fell 0.28 cent to 43.75 cents a gallon. Analysts say trading continues to be driven mostly by technical market factors, as traders await fresh news affecting supply and demand and, particularly, developments involving the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> Exporting Countries. `` The fundamentals are unchanged,'' said <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Gohler </PERSON>, an energy futures broker at <ORGANIZATION> Elders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Even the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>'s weekly report on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> oil inventories, released after the close of trading Tuesday, failed to shake up the market. For the week ended Aug. 19, the API figures showed a decline in crude oil stocks to around 340 million barrels from 344 million the previous week, which normally would be bullish for crude prices.
