<FIRST>r f PM-DrugTests     08-25 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Tests,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Companies Develop On-Site Drug Tests To Cash In On Anti-Drug Trend</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A small <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> company and the local arm of international pharmaceutical giant F. <PERSON> Hoffmann-La </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> hope to profit from the fight against drug abuse, through their disposable drug testing kits. The kits are aimed at law enforcement agencies and businesses that engaged in on-the-spot drug testing, but can be hampered by the time consuming process of having to send samples off to a lab for analysis. <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Screening </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> Blackwood </LOCATION>, is marketing a system called InstaScreen that it says is as easy to use a brewing a cup of coffee _ which is where the idea originated. `` While making a cup of coffee in a Mr. Coffee machine, we said, ` Hey, why not do something like this?' And that was it,'' said <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Akers </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a founder of Drug Screening Systems. `` Quite honestly, it was one of those, ` ah hah!' things,'' he said in an interview. To use the company's device, a urine sample is poured through a disk-shaped filter that collects detectable amounts concentration of any illegal narcotics. The filter is chemically treated to hold any drug traces, and turns the color red if drugs are present. Drug Screening's device likely will face competition from the number of similar tests being created by other companies. One such competitor is <ORGANIZATION> Hoffmann-La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Nutley </LOCATION>, an unit of the Swiss pharmaceutical giant <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hoffmann-La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. <PERSON> Hoffmann-La </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> plans to put its <ORGANIZATION> Ontrak </ORGANIZATION> system on the market in October, said <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Seidner </PERSON>, director of drug abuse marketing for <PERSON> Hoffmann-La </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> subsidiary <ORGANIZATION> Roche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diagnostic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ontrak </ORGANIZATION> costs about $ 2 per test for a specific drug. Urine is placed on a channeled slide and a chemical is added to detect drug traces. The tests come in packages of 40 or 100 and are being tried by criminal justice agencies, said <PERSON> Seidner </PERSON>. Patents have been issued for the <PERSON> Hoffmann-La </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> product, he said. They have been approved for InstaScreen, said <PERSON> Akers </PERSON>' patent lawyer, <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Spivak </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, but not yet issued. InstaScreen kits, which cost about $ 5, contain gloves, two collection cups, strainer, chemical disk and vials. It also includes a bottle for sending positive samples to a lab for confirmation. On-site tests reduce the chance of a mix-up because the samples do not have to be sent to a lab. Also, the tester does not have to wait the usual days or weeks for the sample to be returned. InstaScreen and <ORGANIZATION> Ontrak </ORGANIZATION> also are immune to befuddlement by vinegar or salt, condiments commonly used to mask the presence of drugs. Salt flicked from under a fingernail or vinegar added from a hidden vial prevents most immunoassay tests from working, <PERSON> Akers </PERSON> said. In such tests, antibodies bind with the drug chemicals to register a positive result, but salt and vinegar interfere with the reaction. However, InstaScreen uses chemicals and not antibodies to identify a drug presence, <PERSON> Akers </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hoffmann-La </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON>'s test, although it is an immunoassay, is a type that is not defeated by salt or vinegar, said <PERSON> Seidner </PERSON>. <PERSON> Akers </PERSON> founded Drug Screening with his father <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Akers </PERSON> Sr. in March 1987. The company went public in May with a $ 3 million stock offering. Drug Screening will report its first fiscal year earnings in several weeks, and expects a profit on a projected $ 3 million in sales, said <PERSON> Akers </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
