<HEAD>Sales Slip In Mid-August, But Incentives of Last Year Skew Numbers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sales of domestically-produced cars slipped 18.5 percent in mid-August compared with the same period last year, but analysts said buyer incentives a year ago colored the latest figures. U.S.-made truck sales fell 1.8 percent during the Aug. 11-20 period, making for a 13.2 percent overall decline in sales of vehicles from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories, automakers reported Wednesday. The companies reported selling 298,580 cars and trucks during the period this year, compared with 343,845 vehicles during the same time last year. There were nine selling days in both periods. `` Incentives were just coming in last year and there are no new incentive programs right now,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Healy </PERSON>, an auto industry analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> said the numbers were misleading because of the incentives, and that `` They -LRB- sales -RRB- are very strong.'' <PERSON> Arvid </PERSON> <PERSON> Jouppi </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, disagreed with the strength of the sales. `` The simple story is it's going to take incentives and an early influx of 1989 models to get the sales moving up again,'' he said. Car makers have scheduled their 1989-model introductions through the coming month. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> unveiled its 1989 lineup on Wednesday. `` I would say that there is every indication that the industry has to do one of two things _ get into a very intense share-of-market war or they have got to simply come up with innovative new incentives,'' <PERSON> Jouppi </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> showed the largest decline in the 10-day sales, a 30.3 percent decline to 88,394 cars from 126,887 during the period last year. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s sales fell 10 percent, to 60,184 cars from 66,907 cars last year, and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> sales fell 0.8 percent to 25,985 this month from 26,200 during the period last August. For the year through Aug. 20, each of the Big Three reported increased sales compared with the same period last year; <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> by 1.2 percent, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> by 9.9 percent and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> by 13.7 percent. During the Aug. 11-20 period, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s market share fell to 46.4 percent from 54.3 percent during mid-August of last year. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s market share rose to 31.6 percent from 28.6 percent and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s share moved up to 13.6 percent from 11.2 <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said it sold 9,259 cars during mid-August of this year compared with 7,563 cars in the same period last year _ a 22.4 percent increase. <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION>'s sales fell 4.5 percent during the period from 4,380 cars in mid-August 1987 to 4,182 in the same period this year <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sales </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> reported sales of 1,429 cars during the period this year compared with 1,188 last year, an increase of 20.3 percent.
