<SECOND>PM-Ford-1989, Bjt,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Unveils 1989 Car Line; Projects 6.7 Percent Annual Sales Rise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s 1989 model Thunderbirds and Cougars could help the nation's No. 2 automaker cut further into sales of industry leader <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, according to one analyst. `` Ford has been on a hot streak recently and I would n't be surprised if the new Thunderbird and <PERSON> Cougar </PERSON> allows them to eat some more of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION>'s lunch as far as market share is concerned,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday unveiled the redesigned Thunderbird and Cougar and said it hopes to sell about 1.6 million cars and 1.6 million trucks in 1989, a 6.7 percent increase over this year's projected 3 million total sales Overall, the industry is forecasting a drop from expected sales of 10.4 million cars this year. At a news conference held to coincide with an auto dealer convention in neighboring <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> executives said the company is targeting sales of about 130,000 each for the new Mercury Cougar and Ford Thunderbird, which underwent broad design changes in a five-year, multimillion-dollar development effort. Ten-day <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automotive sales figures released Wednesday gave <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> a 31 percent market share compared with 28 percent last year at this time, while <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> slipped from 54 percent to 45 percent. `` <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s share has been slipping and I would n't be surprised if these new models keep that trend going,'' <PERSON> Healy </PERS