</ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Truck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the reciprocal insurance exchanges managed by Farmers, have agreed to provisions that would assure that the exchanges and their policyholders would not be adversely affected in the merger. Batus began pursuing Farmers in January with a friendly offer of $ 60 a share that was spurned by Farmers' management. Farmers resisted the buyout in hearings before insurance regulators in nine states where the merger needed approval. The company claimed that <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION>, which owns the maker of <LOCATION> Kool </LOCATION> and Viceroy cigarettes, was unlikely to continue Farmers' emphasis on non-smoker insurance discounts. <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> has vowed to continue the discounts. The merger won the approval of insurance regulators in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, and was given conditional approval in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> have rejected the deal and decisions or hearings are pending in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> regulators rejected the merger, but that decision was overturned by a state court.
