<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s merchandise trade deficit spurted 72 percent to a record 2.65 billion pounds, the equivalent of $ 4.5 billion, in July, the government reported Thursday. Immediately after the report was released, the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> signaled a full percentage point increase in the British commercial banks' base lending rate to 12 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Barlcays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Lloyds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Westminster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> quickly responded. That was the eighth time the central bank signaled an increase in the benchmark rate since early June when it stood at a 10-year low of 7.5 percent. All the previous increases had been half-point gains. Stock prices plunged, but the pound, uncertain, darted up and down on the news. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index, which had been down just about 3 points earlier, fell 50.6 points, or 2.8 percent, to 1,768.6 by 2:00 p.m. The pound was quoted at 1.6805 dollars after the news vs. 1.6915 dollars before. Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> said the interest rate hike was necessary and that interest rates would remain at current levels from some time. `` The import figures confirm that the economy has been growing too fast. We have to slow it down and that means higher interest rates,'' <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> said in a <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> radio interview. `` The government is determined to do whatever is necessary to keep inflation under control,'' <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> said. The deficit compared with a revised shortfall off 1.54 billion pounds -LRB- 2.6 billion dollars -RRB- in June and a 1.02 billion-pound -LRB- 1.7 billion-dollar -RRB- gap in July 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> said. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s current account deficit spurted to 2.15 billion pounds -LRB- $ 3.6 billion -RRB- in July, compared with a revised deficit of 1.04 billion pounds -LRB- $ 1.8 billion -RRB- in June and a deficit of 323 million pounds -LRB- $ 546 million -RRB- in July 1987. The current account includes `` invisible'' trade, such as services, overseas investment earnings and official transfer payments, which was estimated to be in surplus by 500 million pounds -LRB- $ 845 million -RRB- in July. July's deficits were much larger than expected by the markets, which had anticipated a merchandise trade gap of 1.51 billion pounds -LRB- $ 2.6 billion -RRB- and a current account deficit of 1.01 billion pounds -LRB- $ 1.7 billion -RRB-. The department originally reported June's trade deficit as 1.52 billion pounds -LRB- $ 2.6 billion -RRB- and the current account deficit as 1.02 billion pounds -LRB- $ 1.7 billion -RRB-.
