<SECOND>PM-Business Travelers,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey Shows 95 Percent of Business Travelers Receive No Training</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A survey revealed that 95 percent of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s business travelers received no training on how to efficiently and effectively travel. In addition, 72 percent of the corporate travel planners said their companies did not provide formal training or orientation about business travel for their employees, according to the survey commissioned by the non-profit <ORGANIZATION> Marriott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Tierney </PERSON>, executive director of the institute, said American business spends more than $ 66 billion annually on business travel and $ 32 billion on training as a whole, but not on traveling. He said many business travelers are not properly prepared for the rigors of travel and become frustrated as soon as they pack their bags. `` This frustration leads to a tired, hassled traveler whose ability to be productive, and to conduct business on the road, can be seriously affected,'' he said. Those frustrations can come from wasted time at airports, hotels and car rental agencies. Untrained travelers often do not request advanced boarding passes for their flights, do n't know that they can ask for rental car express reservation, and fail to use express or video checkout at hotels. `` By understanding these and other basic ins and outs of business travel _ which can be communicated in employee training programs _ business travelers can improve their efficiency and effectiveness, and find the rigors of travel less stressful,'' <PERSON> Tierney </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> MBTI </ORGANIZATION> was established earlier this year to research, observe, monitor and report issues, trends and developments that have an impact on present day business travel. In the survey, the <ORGANIZATION> MBTI </ORGANIZATION> asked 75 business travelers if they had received any formal training or orientation from their employers before they took their first business trip. Those who had not received training then were asked about benefits they would have received if formal training had been offered. The benefits mentioned most were reductions in stress and cost, better use of time, greater productivity and more enjoyment. The corporate travel managers questioned agreed with the benefits and added that a well-trained traveler projects a more professional image.
</TEXT>
