<FIRST>r f BC-Mexico-Economy     08-25 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Mexico-Economy,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer Price Inflation Continues Slide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Consumer prices continue to ease under a tough government anti-inflation program, with prices rising 0.7 percent in the first half of August, the <ORGANIZATION> central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> announced Wednesday night. It predicted smaller increases in consumer prices for the remainder of the month once sales taxes are reduced and other measures taken under the government's Economic Solidarity Pact. The central bank attributed most of the rise in the consumer price index to `` residual effects'' of price hikes for meat and services in the final days of July. `` Without this influence, the Index would have remained practically stable,'' the bank said in a statement. Prices for fruits, fresh vegetables, sugar, personal items and electric appliances actually fell between Aug. 1-15, while rents, at two percent, and clothing, at 1.2 percent, led price gains. The bank forecast even lower inflation for the rest of August because of reductions in the value added tax for basic goods and medicines that went into effect Aug. 18. The government enacted its Economic Solidarity Pact in December as inflation was reaching a record 159.2 percent for all of 1987. A freeze on the peso currency exchange rate, the federal minimum wage and prices for government-regulated goods and services forms the centerpiece of the program. Under the pact, inflation reached 43.3 percent for the first seven months of 1988, while the annual rate since July 1987 was 122.3 percent. On Aug. 14, the government announced modifications to the pact and extended it to Nov. 30, President <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>'s last day in office. While maintaining the freezing of wages, official prices and the peso exchange rate, the government said it would reduce sales taxes from six to zero percent on processed foods and medicines by Sept. 1. It also ordered retailers to reduce prices for their goods an average of 3 percent compared to prices in effect between July 7 and August 7. On Saturday, <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> inspectors closed several <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> pharmacies for failing to abide by the new price guidelines. Commerce Secretary <PERSON> Hector </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Cervantes </PERSON> said Wednesday the government will launch a national media campaign reminding consumers that savings from the sales tax reductions must be reflected in prices at the cash register. The ads will urge consumers to report suspected violations to authorities. The government also plans to publish lists of retailers' prices for thousands of consumer items to compel compliance with the pact, <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Cervantes </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
