<FIRST>u f PM-InterestRates     08-25 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Interest Rates,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Germans Raise Key Interest Rates; Other Europeans Follow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s central bank raised a key interest rate today to 3.5 percent from 3 percent because of the stronger dollar, and central banks in several Western European countries quickly followed. The action marked the latest in a round of higher interest rates worldwide and came a few weeks after the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> tightened credit in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by pushing interest rates higher. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency slumped in response to the action today by the West German <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> and other European banks. The dollar was quoted at around 1.8660 West German marks at midmorning in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, down sharply from 1.8820 marks late Wednesday. In <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> signaled a full percentage point increase in the British commercial banks' base lending rate to 12 percent, following a government report on the country's trade deficit in July. The report showed the July trade gap soared 72 percent to a record 2.65 billion pounds, or about $ 4.5 billion. The central banks of <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> announced interest rate hikes shortly after the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> move. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, however, a senior <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> official said there is `` absolutely no need to consider an adjustment in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s monetary policy just because the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> raised their base rates.'' The higher West German discount rate goes into effect on Friday, the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement. The discount rate is the interest the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> charges on loans to other banks. The <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> was selling dollars in the open market shortly after making its announcement, according to currency dealers in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION>, cited the weakness of the West German mark against the dollar as a reason for lifting the key rate, which makes mark-denominated investments more attractive. `` Today's step is an important signal which will be understood by the foreign-exchange and capital markets,'' <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON> said. `` It should lead to stabilization of the -LRB- currency -RRB- and capital markets and the first reactions should show this is the case.'' Following the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> action, the dollar slid to 1.8640 marks at the <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> currency exchange in early afternoon. Earlier, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency had fallen to an official <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> fixing of 1.8764 marks from Wednesday's official level of 1.8960 marks. <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON> told reporters that the dollar's strength against the mark endangered efforts to adjust trade imbalances between the world's major trading partners He also said the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> will `` continue to do everything to stem the decline of the mark against the dollar.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> president also said the discount rate increase was aimed at curbing West German inflation and bringing the country's above-target money supply growth back into the proper range. The <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> has adjusted domestic interest rates upwards three times in the past eight weeks.
</TEXT>
