<HEAD>GNP Strong, Inflation Rises, Foreign Interest Rates Up, Home Sales
Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with interest-rate hikes
abroad, home sales report and stock market reax. Picks up 9th graf
pvs, The difference ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s economy and corporate profits expanded briskly this spring, the government said today, but the news was overshadowed by higher inflation, rising interest rates, slumping financial markets and a slowdown in home sales. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the gross national product, the broadest measure of economic health, rose at an annual rate of 3.3 percent from April through June despite severe shock from the drought that seared much of the country. The GNP rate of expansion was unchanged from the first quarter. Without the drought, the GNP would have shot up at a 4.3 percent annual rate in the April-June period. The government also said after-tax corporate profits shot up 11.5 percent in the second quarter following a 2.5 percent rise in the first quarter. The performance was the best since a 14.5 percent rise in the 1983 second quarter. But April-June inflation as measured by a GNP price index rose at an annual rate of 5.1 percent, the fastest increase since a 5.8 percent rise in the third quarter of 1982, the department said. The surge was blamed on higher prices for clothes, food and fuel. Further obscuring the GNP and corporate profit news was that key West European nations raised interest rates today, blaming the move on the stronger <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar and consequent weakness in their own currencies. The increases signaled another round of higher interest rates worldwide. Those developments helped incite a selloff in the bond market, a sensitive barometer of interest rates and the economy. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s key 30-year issue fell nearly $ 7.50 per $ 1,000 in face amount and its yield rose to 9.46 percent from 9.39 percent late Wednesday. On Wall Street, where traders were recalling the stock market peak a year ago today, prices slid as well. The Dow Jones industrial average was down about 18 points to the 2,008 level by late morning. Rising interest rates also played a key role in a 5 percent drop in existing single-family home sales last month, a real estate trade group said today. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION> said the decline was partly the result of higher mortgage costs. The developments came a day after the government reported <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s trade deficit shrank 15 percent in the April-June quarter, which heartened Republicans fighting to retain the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> but did n't impress the financial markets. The difference between what the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> spends and sells abroad narrowed to a deficit of $ 29.9 billion in the second quarter, compared with a $ 35.2 billion deficit in the first quarter. Many economists regard the trade deficit as one of the most visible weaknesses in the economy, reflecting a relentless addiction to cheap imports and consequent difficulty for domestic companies trying to compete. Democrats have attempted to make the trade deficit an issue in the presidential campaign. But the improvement reported Wednesday suggested <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers were making strong gains in selling abroad. Some economists are predicting the trade deficit will drop by nearly 25 percent for the entire year, marking the first annual improvement since President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> took office. Republicans are hoping voters will focus on the improvement, which already has shown up in the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s monthly merchandise trade reports. In other economic news, major automakers said Wednesday that mid-August sales of U.S.-made cars and trucks fell by 13.2 percent from the same period a year earlier, when sales were inflated by buyers taking advantage of dealer incentives.
