<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge today denied motions for a new trial for a <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> entrepreneur, the former president of the <ORGANIZATION> Seven-Up </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and a soft drink bottler who had been convicted of price fixing. <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lapides </PERSON>, 57, chairman of the board of <ORGANIZATION> Alleghany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beverage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Cheverly </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harford </PERSON>, former president of <ORGANIZATION> Mid-Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bottling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Silver </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Spring </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> Alleghany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bottling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> were convicted following a six-week trial in April and May. <PERSON> Lapides </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harford </PERSON> face a maximum three years in prison. <ORGANIZATION> Alleghany </ORGANIZATION> faces a maximum $ 1 million fine. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON> was expected to impose sentences today. `` I am very concerned with restitution to the public,'' <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON> said. `` People who believe money is the answer to any crime because they are a corporation should think differently when they enter this court.' At the time of his conviction, <PERSON> Harford </PERSON> was the president of <ORGANIZATION> Seven-Up </ORGANIZATION>, but resigned that post three days after the conviction. <PERSON> Harford </PERSON>'s conviction was the result of actions while heading the <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> bottling firm, and did not involve Seven-Up. The convictions were part of an on-going <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> probe of the soft drink industry, which has resulted in 11 grand jury investigations in eight other states. <PERSON> Lapides </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harford </PERSON> were convicted of rigging the wholesale price of their respective products in 1983 and 1984. <ORGANIZATION> Alleghany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beverage </ORGANIZATION> was the parent company of <ORGANIZATION> Alleghany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bottling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> until 1985 when <PERSON> Lapides </PERSON> sold the subsidiary for $ 160 million. During the trial, the defense contended that neither man knew of the scheme and that if the allegations were true, then it was the work of lower level employees who made decisions without their bosses' knowledge. Federal prosecutors argued that the two bottlers reached an accord to halt the previous bitter competition by fixing the wholesale price of their products sold to schools, motels, hotels, and other commercial buyers in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Virgina </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> pleaded guilty to earlier, similar indictments and agreed to pay $ 2 million in fines for price rigging in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, markets. In March, both bottling firms also agreed to rebate $ 45,000 to <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> to be distributed to school districts for overcharges on their soft drink purchases. The agreement drawn up by Attorney General <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> called for <LOCATION> Mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> to pay $ 30,000 and <ORGANIZATION> Alleghany </ORGANIZATION> $ 15,000. Prior to the April conviction, several other soft drink executives have been found guilty or pleaded guilty to a variety of charges. In February 1987, <PERSON> Armand </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gravely </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> division manager for <ORGANIZATION> Alleghany </ORGANIZATION>, was convicted of price fixing and obstruction of justice. He was sentenced to four months in jail and fined $ 15,000. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wynns </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> vice president, pleaded guilty in May 1987 to charges he lied to the grand jury investigating the price fixing. The former president of <ORGANIZATION> Alleghany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bottling </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Timonium </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, was given a 3-year sentence, with all but 120 days suspended, and fined $ 45,000 in August 1987 after pleading guilty to price fixing. A third executive indicted along with <PERSON> Lapides </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harford </PERSON>, <PERSON> Odis </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> vice president, pleaded guilty to price fixing in March.
