<HEAD>Pentagon Thinks Illegal Exports Aided Soviet Fighter Production</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to update. A version moving on general news
wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said today it believes the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s jet fighter program has benefitted from the diversion of <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> milling equipment in a case of illegal exporting that rivals the wrongdoing by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said a French concern by the name of <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> is under investigation by authorities in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` The investigation involves the alleged diversion of dozens of very sophisticated milling machines to military users in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> added. `` We believe the machines were used in the Soviet MiG -LRB- jet fighter -RRB- program.'' <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> was asked about the investigation after another top <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> official, <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryen </PERSON>, told a group of <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> reporters Wednesday that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities have been deeply involved in investigating a `` serious'' technology diversion case. <PERSON> Bryen </PERSON>, the deputy undersecretary of defense for trade security policy, refused at the time to identify the company under investigation. He said only that American investigators were receiving `` splendid cooperation'' in the matter; that some individuals already had been charged and other arrests would follow, and that he hoped to make more information available in a few months. Other government sources then disclosed Wednesday the investigation concerned a French company known as Forest Line that once went by the name of <PERSON> Ratier-Forest </PERSON>, and that information was subsequently acknowledged by <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>. `` The case ... involves a French company which is currently under investigation by the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> government,'' said <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>. `` The company name is Forest Line.'' The other sources, who insisted on anonymity, said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence agents tipped the French early this year about alleged Forest Line sales of heavy milling equipment to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` There has been good cooperation,'' said one source. `` We shared information with them and they moved quickly.'' The French case surfaced last spring but attracted little notice then. French authorities disclosed in April that four people had been arrested under anti-espionage laws, including <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Tardy </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francaises </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lourdes </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Jean-Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamouton </PERSON>, president of Forest Line. Machines <PERSON> Francaises </PERSON> <PERSON> Lourdes </PERSON>, now bankrupt, was the parent company of <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION>, which specialized in manufacturing heavy tool equipment. No trials have been held, and the status of the cases is unclear. The <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> scandal came to a head earlier this year when the <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a majority-owned subsidiary, was found guilty in a Japanese court of illegally trading high-tech items with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The firm was convicted of selling sophisticated milling machines to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in the early 1980s. The machines can be used to fashion quiet submarine propellers. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military experts claim the <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> sale has complicated dramatically the task of locating Russian subs. <PERSON> Bryen </PERSON>, while never naming the company now under investigation, drew attention to the matter Wednesday when asked if the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> had become involved in any other major export probes since <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION>. `` There's even a bigger one, but it's different,'' <PERSON> Bryen </PERSON> replied. `` It's a different kind of case because, first of all, we've had splendid cooperation on it. There's more, much more involved than the <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> case. `` It's certainly serious and it's in a different field; it's in the aerospace area,'' he said. `` It's under investigation and there have already been some equivalent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> indictments on the case, in another country. There's going to be some others. `` But I'm going to be real cagey on this because I do n't want to spring it yet. But I think in the next few months we should be prepared to describe it in more detail.'' Asked if any <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> citizens were known to be involved, he replied: `` Not that I know of at the moment.'' The Toshiba incident helped lead to enactment of new trade legislation and sanctions against that company in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as well as a Japanese government overhaul of export licensing procedures. Last fall, when revelations about the <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> case were surfacing, a Norwegian police investigation found that several <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> companies _ including <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> _ had conspired to divert sensitive technology to the Soviets dating back to the 1970s. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sources said Wednesday, however, that the current investigation involved equipment sales that continued at least through 1986 and possibly 1987 _ long after the last <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> transaction. `` That's what makes it serious,'' one source said. The Forest Line equipment, said to include huge milling machinery that can be used to fabricate aircraft fuselages and jet engine turbine blades, was allegedly sold to the Soviets after corporate executives submitted fraudulent applications for export licenses, the sources said. <PERSON> Bryen </PERSON> told reporters the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has made great strides in clamping down on the exports of sensitive military technology to the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc and in convincing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allies to do the same.
