<FIRST>u f AM-JapaneseSinging Bjt   08-25 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japanese Singing, Bjt,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>Americans Sing for Success in Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If the thought of giving an after-dinner speech makes you nervous, singing in a foreign language for prospective clients might cause you to lose your appetite. <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> <PERSON> Fujiyama </PERSON> did not like the idea, but after socializing with Japanese clients, he realized American business skills were not enough to assure success in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. He spoke Japanese, but, he says, he needed to learn to sing it. `` If you're going to succeed as a businessman, you have to do business the way they do it, and in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, everybody sings,'' says <PERSON> Fujiyama </PERSON>. `` Everybody from the ordinary salary worker to the corporate presidents and executives.'' The songfests usually begin after a business meeting or social gathering, he says, when the company's executives take their turn at the microphone singing popular Japanese tunes. After they are finished, their guests, such as <PERSON> Fujiyama </PERSON>, are invited to give it a go. `` For you to refuse is a great insult, but to sing badly is even worse,'' he says. So <PERSON> Fujiyama </PERSON> began to practice, first by singing along in his car with `` karaoke'' tapes, which are high-quality instrumental versions of popular songs. Later, one of his Japanese clients gave him with an elaborate sound system for his downtown <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> office, complete with laser disk, two tape players and an oversized video screen so he could watch his technique. A star was not quite born, but <PERSON> Fujiyama </PERSON> swears he is improving. `` I still do n't want to sing out in public, but I've gotten better. I can carry a tune now,'' he says. <PERSON> Fujiyama </PERSON> can not explain the cultural differences that cause Japanese _ young and old _ to sing at home along with variety shows -LRB- which flash the lyrics on the television screen -RRB- and at `` karaoke'' bars with professional equipment, light shows and audiences; while Americans tend to sing in their cars with the windows rolled up and are relieved when they manage `` Happy Birthday'' without embarrassing themselves. But <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Feltz </PERSON>, who specializes in Japanese culture at the <ORGANIZATION> East-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> here, has some ideas. `` Japanese, as in many countries, are not as ashamed of singing as we are in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' says <PERSON> Feltz </PERSON>, who as an ethnomusicologist studies music of <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> cultures. `` There you're not expected to sing like <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Springsteen </PERSON> or <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> <PERSON> Sills </PERSON>. In many <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> cultures, <PERSON> Feltz </PERSON> says, people have a common repertoire and sing songs they learned as children for their entire lives. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, he said, more emphasis is put on the quality, so elementary school students who once belted out `` My country' t is of thee ...'' with abandon learn to be self-conscious and clam up as they grow older That's what happened to <PERSON> Adrian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mangiboyat </PERSON>, 32, who left his job as a reporter for the <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> here to teach English in a Japanese village. `` I guess I sang at school as a little kid, but I outgrew that. I never sang along with the radio, in the shower, nothing like that,'' he says. `` But when I applied for the job -LRB- in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> -RRB- they said singing was an integral part of Japanese culture, and I knew I was in trouble.'' <PERSON> Mangiboyat </PERSON> earned the teaching position in a program sponsored by the Japanese government, but before he departed for <PERSON> Yabuki-Machi </PERSON>, a small town 100 miles north of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, he enrolled at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hawaii </ORGANIZATION>. In a nine-week course called `` Voice Training for the Tone Deaf,'' Mangiboyat and other would-be warblers spent two hours a week learning scales, pitch and simple songs. Their homework included taking the stage at a local `` karaoke'' bar popular with Japanese tourists. `` The Japanese officials said being able to sing will give me an edge with my students and the other villagers. It will show them that I really tried to learn about their culture.'' <PERSON> Fujiyama </PERSON> agrees. `` By asking you to sing with them, they're saying ` let's be friends.'''
</TEXT>
