<SECOND>BC-Germany-Rate Hike,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>West German Central Bank Raises Key Interest Rate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s central bank raised a key interest rate Thursday to defend the value of its currency and fend off inflation, leading a round of rate hikes in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> raised its discount rate, which it charges on loans to other banks, by half a percentage point to 3.5 percent. <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION>, cited the weakness of the mark against the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar as a main reason for lifting the discount rate. The higher discount rate should cause other interest rates to rise. That would support the exchange value of the mark by making mark-denominated investments more attractive. The dollar eased more than a pfennig to level around 1.8650 marks soon after the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION>'s announcement. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> followed the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION>'s lead and raised rates. `` Today's step is an important signal which will be understood by the foreign exchange and capital markets,'' <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON> told reporters that the dollar's strength against the mark endangered efforts to adjust trade imbalances between the world's major trading partners He also said the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> will `` continue to do everything to stem the decline of the mark against the dollar.'' <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON> also said the discount rate increase was aimed at curbing inflation and bringing the country's above-target money supply growth back into the proper range. The mark's weakness has contributed to inflation by raising import prices. The <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> decided to keep its Lombard rate steady at 5 percent, and indicated no change in its rate on securities repurchase agreements. The <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> has adjusted German interest rates upwards three times in the past eight weeks. It raised the Lombard rate to 5 percent from 4.5 percent on July 28, following a hike in the discount rate to 3 percent from 2.5 percent on June 30.
