<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stocks fell sharply Thursday following news of a British trade deficit in July that was nearly double market expectations and a subsequent hike in British interest rates. A sagging start on Wall Street also depressed share prices. The <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times-Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> 100-share index fell 39 points, or 2.1 percent, to close at 1,780.2. Earlier in the afternoon, the index was down more than 50 points. Volume was a relatively strong 399.3 million shares by midafternoon. Following the trade figure release, the Bank of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> signaled a 1 percentage point hike to 12 percent in the British commercial banks' base lending rate. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s merchandise trade deficit spurted to a record 2.65 billion pounds, equivalent to $ 4.5 billion, in July, compared with a revised shortfall of $ 1.54 billion in June. The country's current account deficit, which includes invisible trade such as overseas investment earnings as well as merchandise trade, spurted to 2.15 billion pounds in July, compared with a revised deficit of 1.04 billion pounds in June.
