<SECOND>AM-Britain-Economy, Bjt,0741</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Interest Rates Raised Following Record Trade Deficit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The British government, trying to curb inflation, on Thursday pushed up interest rates to a 2 -LCB- - year high after announcing a record trade deficit for July that was nearly double the previous record The July deficit and the interest-rate hike, both unexpectedly large, rocked British financial markets. Share prices plummeted on the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and trading volume picked up. The British pound first fell on the trade news, and then had a mixed reaction to the interest-rate hike. The British rate rise came amid a round of key interest-rate increases in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s central bank, raised its discount rate by half a percentage point to 3.5 percent. The central banks of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> followed the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION>, hiking their own key rates. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times-Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> 100-share index, which plunged more than 50 points before recovering some of its losses, closed 39 points, or 2.1 percent, lower at 1,768.6, amid moderate trading volume. The pound soared to $ 1.6995 late Thursday from $ 1.6788 late Wednesday, but it fell to 3.16 West German marks from 3.17 marks. The Bank of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> signaled a full percentage point increase in the commercial banks' base lending rate to 12 percent, soon after the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> reported that <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s merchandise trade deficit soared in July to a record 2.65 billion pounds, or about $ 4.5 billion The previous record trade gap was 1.7 billion pounds, or around $ 2.9 billion, in May. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s four leading commercial banks _ <ORGANIZATION> Barclays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Lloyds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Westminster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> _ quickly responded to the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s signal. Many market watchers had anticipated an increase of only half a percentage point in the base lending rate. It was the eighth increase in the benchmark rate since early June, when the rate stood at a 10-year low of 7.5 percent, and it brought the base lending rate to its highest level since January 1986. The previous hikes were half-point increases, with the most recent coming on Aug. 8. `` The import figures confirm that the economy has been growing too fast. We have to slow it down and that means higher interest rates,'' Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> said. Spurred by <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s strong consumer spending, imports jumped 13 percent, across the board, to 9.43 billion pounds, or about $ 16 billion, in July, while exports fell 0.9 percent to 6.78 billion pounds, or $ 11.5 billion. `` The government is determined to do whatever is necessary to keep inflation under control,'' <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> said in a <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> radio interview. `` The economy as a whole is doing extremely well,'' he added. The full-point interest-rate hike was viewed as a major additional tightening of monetary policy to help reduce the growing inflationary pressures in the economy. Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> has repeatedly said that reducing such pressures is her top economic priority. Inflation in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> increased to an annual rate of 4.8 percent in July from 4.6 percent in June. A spate of recent economic reports has confirmed faster-than-expected growth in the British economy. On Tuesday, for example, the goverment reported that <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s inflation-adjusted gross domestic product, measured by the output of goods and services, rose 1.3 percent in the second quarter from the first The markets had expected a rise of only 1 percent. Recent weakness in the pound, exacerbated by the latest trade report, has given the <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> government room to increase interest rates without pushing the pound dangerously high, which would hurt British exports even more. `` We now have a genuine balance-of-payments crisis. These figures are appalling,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Shepperd </PERSON>, director of the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Warburg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, referring to the July trade report. The latest trade deficit compared with a 1.02 billion pound, or $ 1.7 billion, gap in July 1987. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s current-account deficit jumped to 2.15 billion pounds in July, up from a revised deficit of 1.04 billion pounds in June and a deficit of 323 million pounds in July 1987. The current account includes `` invisible'' trade, such as services, foreign investment earnings and official transfer payments, which was estimated to be in surplus by 500 million pounds in July.
