<FIRST>a f BC-BehindtheWheel Adv03-04   08-25 0840</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Behind the Wheel, Adv 03-04,0870</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 03</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Sept. 3-4 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Grand AM Is No Typical 4-Cylinder</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto and LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's not often that a compact car with a four-cylinder engine can offer a decent sporty-car ride. But the 1988 Pontiac Grand AM SE is no typical four-cylinder compact. For starters, the standard 2-liter, fuel-injected engine is turbocharged and can produce 165 horspower. <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION> adds it can go from 0 to 60 in a brisk eight seconds. The Grand AM SE's standard suspension package includes <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eagle </ORGANIZATION> GT +4 all-season radial tires and stabilizer bars that make for a firm, stable ride Inside, there's a sporty feel with the thick, leather-wrapped steering wheel, contoured front bucket seats _ molded to hold your body in place _ and turbo boost gauge set amid a sporty driver area. Outside, the Grand AM SE is one of the prettiest of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s cars, with bumpers and front, side and rear skirts that match the body so there's no gaudy chrome. In fact, the styling, which debuted in the 1985 model year, helps explain why the Grand AM is the <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION> Division's volume leader. From the buyer's perspective, it has snazzy styling, said <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION> spokesman <PERSON> Reggie </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>. Exterior styling and cost are the two main reasons cited by buyers, he added. The lowest-priced Grand AM is $ 10,269, including $ 400 for shipping, <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said. But the SE test car totaled just under $ 15,000. That $ 10,000 - $ 15,000 price range encompasses many of the Grand AM's competitors, such as the <ORGANIZATION> Buick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Skylark </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lancer </ORGANIZATION>, which start around $ 10,400, and the <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> Prelude, which starts around $ 13,600 <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> noted the Grand AM _ which comes in three versions, the Grand AM, the LE and the SE _ is particularly adept at luring young buyers. Median age of buyers is 32, with 63 percent under age 35, <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said. Forty-even percent are male, 55 percent are married and 38 percent have college education. Median income is $ 40,000 annually. The test car, an SE, was fun to drive. The suspension and engine, linked to a three-speed automatic transmission, offered somewhat of a muscle-car ride complete with throaty rumble from under the hood during hard accelerations. Handling was admirable, even at high speeds. There was no roll, no sway. The trunk was roomy, and the rear seats split and folded down for more storage space. There were nice touches inside for driver and passengers. Map lights were available in front and rear. Front visors had slits in the material to slip paper, maps, etc., and netting on the back of the front seats offered spots for newspapers, magazines for rear-seat passengers. Controls for the AM-FM stereo and cassette player as well as ventilation were conveniently located at the front of the center console. Fit and finish inside and out was excellent. I noticed a few problems, too. At 5-foot-4, I found it difficult to put the seat belt into its latch alongside the driver seat once I had the seat moved up to where I could touch the pedals comfortably. The seat belt latch was jammed between the driver seat and the center console storage area. It was also difficult to unlatch the belt without first moving the driver seat back a ways, for the same reason. The Grand AM has a cruise control system found in many other <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> cars that is mounted on the turn signal stalk. As with the other <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> cars, I sometimes discovered the lever in the on position even when the cruise was n't actuated. Still, it's unsettling to glance down and see it on. Rear seating, for three, might be snug. The car also gulped down the gasoline. Fuel economy is rated at 20 miles per gallon in the city and 27 mpg on the highway, but in my demanding city-highway driving I did n't get 20. Lastly, the center console had yellow spots that would light up to indicate what gear the automatic transmission was in. But in bright sunlight, it was murder trying to see what gear the shifter had settled in. Consumer Reports says the 1986 Grand AM with four-cylinder engine, the latest model it has information for, had an average record for trouble, up from worse-han-average for the 1985 model. Still, 1988 looks to be the best year for Grand AM yet, with projections of 220,000 sales compared with 216,065 in the 1987 model year and 190,994 in the 1986 model year. We're in great shape for that car line, <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said, noting sales have been on target. He said even <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Kay </PERSON>, the cosmetics company, has ordered a fleet of 5,000 Grand AMs for its employees. But he quickly added they wo n't be pink.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Job </PERSON>, former executive business editor of The <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, writes biweekly automobile reviews for The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. She has covered the automobile industry for six years.
</TEXT>
