<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices posted some broad losses today, weighed down by worries about rising interest rates. The level of trading was up from the previous session, but was still relatively sluggish. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which climbed 37.34 points on Wednesday, was down 26.31 to 2,000.36 with two hours left in the session. Today's decline comes on the first anniversary of the Dow Jones industrial average reaching its record close of 2,722.42 on Aug. 25, 1987. Declining issues outpaced gainers by a margin of nearly 11 to 3 among issues listed on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, with 324 up, 1,071 down and 483 unchanged. <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> volume amounted to 91.26 million shares at 2 p.m. on Wall Street compared with 84.44 million shares at the same point Wednesday. Analysts said stocks suffered from renewed interest rate worries. Before the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stock market opened today, the West German central bank raised a key lending rate and banks in several other European countries followed suit. Analysts said the increase in European rates stirred speculation that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rates could also be headed higher. That hurt stocks because higher rates could cut corporate profits and make government notes and bonds more attractive. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government today revised upward its estimate of second-quarter economic growth to 3.3 percent rate from 3.1 percent. Prices in the bond market moved lower, pushing interest rates higher. The 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond, for instance, was down about $ 6.25 for every $ 1,000 in face value, while its yield jumped to 9.46 percent from 9.40 percent late Wednesday. Among active issues on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> fell 1 -RCB- to 111, <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> was down -LCB- at 42 \, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> was down -RCB- to 28 and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> was down | at 39 -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> Insilco </ORGANIZATION> rose 1 -LRB- to 31 -LRB-. Its board approved a buyout offer of $ 31.75 a share. In over-the-counter trading, <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> was up -RCB- at 70. The company agreed to a $ 75-a-share takeover offer from B.A.T. Industries of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, but some obstacles remain to completing the deal. The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> index was off 1.55 at 146.38. On the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the composite market value index fell 1.24 to 292.82.
