<HEAD>Grain, Soybeans Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures prices ended mixed to slightly higher Thursday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. Analysts described the day as `` featureless'' because few signs of confirmation could be found for a pair of rumors that strongly influenced trading one day earlier. Soybeans were pressured at the opening as speculation that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> was planning a big soyoil purchase under the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> export bonus program failed to gain support. There was some firming up late, however, as the beans closed mostly higher. Wheat climbed across the board on talk of increased export bonus business, despite the fact that reports Wednesday of a completed one-year extension of the grain accord between the Soviets and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> appear to have been premature. On the close, wheat was 2 -RCB- cents to 4 cents higher, with the contract for delivery in September at $ 3.93 -LCB- a bushel; corn was 4 -RCB- cents lower to 1 -LCB- cents higher, with September at $ 2.81 a bushel; oats were 1 cent lower to -LCB- cent higher, with September at $ 2.54 -LCB-; and soybeans were 5 cents lower to 6 cents higher, with September at $ 8.35 a bushel.
