<HEAD>News Corp. Fourth Quarter Net Down 67.5 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, a vast communications conglomerate with holdings that range from British newspapers to the <ORGANIZATION> Fox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, reported a 67.5 percent drop in fourth-quarter earnings Thursday, attributing the results to <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> startup costs and a big decline in asset sales Excluding those factors, <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said, its earnings rose 41 percent from the comparable period a year earlier. The company, based in <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, and controlled by publishing-entertainment entrepreneur <PERSON> Rupert </PERSON> <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON>, earned $ 128.1 million in the three months ended June 30, vs. $ 394.4 million a year earlier. Earnings for the previous quarter and year were inflated by more than $ 300 million in special gains, largely property sales. Earnings per share for the latest quarter, stated in American Depositary Receipts listed on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, were 82 cents vs. $ 2.61 a year earlier. An ADR represents two of the company's ordinary shares. The company said fourth-quarter revenue totaled $ 1.2 billion, up 22.3 percent from $ 981.3 million. In a statement from its <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> office, <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> based the figures on what it called the average rates of exchange between <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollars and Australian dollars prevailing in each period. For the year, <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said earnings totaled $ 341.27 million, or $ 2.20 per ADR, a 37.3 percent decline from the $ 544.43 million, or $ 3.72 per ADR, earned in fiscal 1987. Revenue totaled $ 4.35 billion, vs. $ 3.5 billion, a 24.2 percent increase. <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is a diversified international media and entertainment company with primary interests in newspapers, magazines, book publishing, movie and television production and distribution, and commercial printing. Principal operations are in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Besides <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>, which the company is attempting to build into the fourth major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> network, <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> holdings include <ORGANIZATION> Metromedia </ORGANIZATION> TV stations and number of magazines and newspapers, among them the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Antonio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express-News </ORGANIZATION>. Most recently the company acquired <ORGANIZATION> Triangle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, publisher of <ORGANIZATION> TV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guide </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seventeen </ORGANIZATION>, for $ 3 billion.
