<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     08-25 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0221</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices pulled back today after a big rise in the previous session, as worries about rising interest rates took a toll. But prices finished above the day's lows and trading remained sluggish. Today's decline came on the first anniversary of the Dow Jones industrial average reaching a record high. Before the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stock market opened today, the West German central bank raised a key lending rate and banks in several other European countries followed suit. Analysts said the increases stirred speculation that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rates could also be headed higher. That hurt stocks because higher rates make government securities more attractive to investors. Also, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government today revised upward its estimate of second-quarter economic growth to 3.3 percent rate from 3.1 percent, and boosted a measure of inflation tied to the gross national product figure. Prices in the bond market moved lower, pushing interest rates higher. The 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond, for instance, lost about $ 5 for every $ 1,000 in face value, while its yield rose to 9.44 percent from 9.40 percent late Wednesday. Analysts said yields on shorter-term government issues were also tempting investors to stay on the sidelines until the interest rate outlook clarifies.
</TEXT>
