<FIRST>r f AM-Farmers-Batus     08-25 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farmers-Batus,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmers-Batus Agreement Ends Eight-Year Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s agreement to be bought by <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 5.2 billion ends a bitter eight-month battle that included unusual skirmishing over the evils of smoking and investment in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Spokesmen for the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> insurer and the <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, tobacco and retailing conglomerate could n't say Thursday just how many lawsuits and administrative proceedings have been spawned by their fight. But the merger deal, which was announced late Wednesday, calls for the companies to cooperate in unraveling the tangle and cooperating in pressing for approval of the purchase by insurance regulators in various states. Farmers agreed to be bought by <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> for $ 75 a share, $ 3 a share higher than <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION>' highest previous publicly announced offer and $ 12 more a share than <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> has been offering stockholders on the market. No date has been set for a needed vote on the merger by shareholders of Farmers, the nations' third-largest home and auto insurer and seventh-biggest property and casualty insurer. <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION>, the American subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> BAT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, owns <ORGANIZATION> Brown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Williamson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, maker of <LOCATION> Kool </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Viceroy </PERSON> and other brands, Appleton Papers and retailiers including <PERSON> Sak </PERSON>'s Fifth Avenue and <LOCATION> Marshall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION>'s. The deal requires the approval of insurance regulators in nine of the states where Farmers does business, and hearings before those regulators were the forum for the most acrimonious accusations in the takover battle. Farmers representatives maintained that <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION>, as a tobacco producer, would end non-smoker discounts for Farmers policy holders. When <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> vowed to continue the discounts, Farmers suggested ownership by <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> would prevent it from crusading against smoking as strongly as it has in the past. Farmers also lined up numerous local, state and national elected officials to blast <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION>' British parent, <ORGANIZATION> BAT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, for maintaining businesses in racially segregated <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. After the deal was cut, <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> said the earlier acrimony had n't effected the week-long negotiations. `` I think often things that are said in court are much more acrimonious than one's true feelings,'' <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> said in an interview. One or the other of the companies has challenged or threatened to challenge the seven state regulatory decisions issued to date, some in court and some in appeals to the regulators. By dropping various lawsuits and jointly appealing regulators' decisions, the companies said, officials believe they can clear the regulatory path to a merger as early as the end of the year The merger won the approval of insurance regulators in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, and was given conditional approval in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> have rejected the deal and decisions or hearings are pending in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> regulators rejected the merger, but that decision was overturned by a state court.
</TEXT>
