<HEAD>Former Coke Bottler Sentenced To Six Months In Price-Fixing
Conspiracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A prominent <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> entrepreneur and the former president of The <ORGANIZATION> Seven-Up </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> each were sentenced to the maximum three years in prison and fined $ 100,000 Thursday for their part in a price-fixing conspiracy. <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lapides </PERSON>, 57, chairman of the board of <ORGANIZATION> Alleghany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beverage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Cheverly </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harford </PERSON>, former president of <LOCATION> Mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> Coca-Cola Bottling of Silver Spring, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, were convicted in May following a six-week trial. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON> suspended all but 179 days of <PERSON> Lapides </PERSON>' sentence and all but six months of <PERSON> Harford </PERSON>'s sentence. <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON> also placed both men on three years' probation after the completion of their sentence, with each required to perform community service during that period. <PERSON> Harford </PERSON> has appealed his conviction and <PERSON> Lapides </PERSON> is expected to do so. The federal jury had found that <PERSON> Harford </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Alleghany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bottling </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Lapides </PERSON>, as head of <ORGANIZATION> Alleghany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bottling </ORGANIZATION>'s parent company, conspired to fix the wholesale price of <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi-Cola </ORGANIZATION> products. Sentencing for the corporation will continue Friday, and <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON> said proceedings could take several days. When convicted, <PERSON> Harford </PERSON> was the president of <ORGANIZATION> Seven-Up </ORGANIZATION>, but resigned that post three days later. <PERSON> Harford </PERSON>'s conviction was the result of actions while heading the <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> bottling firm and did not involve Seven-Up. The convictions were part of an on-going <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> probe of the soft drink industry, which has resulted in 11 grand jury investigations in eight other states. <PERSON> Lapides </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harford </PERSON> were convicted of rigging the wholesale price of their respective products in 1983 and 1984. <ORGANIZATION> Alleghany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beverage </ORGANIZATION> was the parent company of <ORGANIZATION> Alleghany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bottling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> until 1985 when <PERSON> Lapides </PERSON> sold the subsidiary for $ 160 million. During the trial, the defense contended neither man knew of the scheme and that if the allegations were true it was the work of lower level employees who made decisions without their bosses' knowledge Federal prosecutors argued the two bottlers reached an accord to halt the previous bitter competition by fixing the wholesale price of their products sold to schools, motels, hotels, and other commercial buyers in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> pleaded guilty to earlier, similar indictments and agreed to pay $ 2 million in fines for price rigging in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, markets. In March, both bottling firms also agreed to rebate $ 45,000 to <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> to be distributed to school districts for overcharges on their soft drink purchases. The agreement drawn up by Attorney General <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> called for <LOCATION> Mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> to pay $ 30,000 and <ORGANIZATION> Alleghany </ORGANIZATION> $ 15,000. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> had argued <PERSON> Harford </PERSON> be given the maximum sentence because `` he is the highest culpable official at <LOCATION> Mid-Atlantic </LOCATION>. `` We should not allow this case with such tremendous damage to the public to be a source of cynicism to the public'' by giving <PERSON> Harford </PERSON> a light sentence, he said. During the hearing, <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON> said he had received numerous letters from friends, relatives and business associates on <PERSON> Harford </PERSON>'s outstanding achievements in the community In his sentencing, the judge commended <PERSON> Harford </PERSON> for his work in the community, and for his persistent urging of <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> to become more involved. `` Your company did a lot of good for the community through your urgings, but you were being charitible to the public with money you took from the public,'' he said. Prior to the conviction, several other soft drink executives have been found guilty or pleaded guilty to a variety of charges. In February 1987, <PERSON> Armand </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gravely </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> division manager for <ORGANIZATION> Alleghany </ORGANIZATION>, was convicted of price fixing and obstruction of justice. He was sentenced to four months in jail and fined $ 15,000. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wynns </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> vice president, pleaded guilty in May 1987 to charges he lied to the grand jury investigating the price fixing. The former president of <ORGANIZATION> Alleghany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bottling </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Timonium </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, was given a 3-year sentence, with all but 120 days suspended, and fined $ 45,000 in August 1987 after pleading guilty to price fixing. A third executive indicted along with <PERSON> Lapides </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harford </PERSON>, <PERSON> Odis </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> vice president, pleaded guilty to price fixing in March.
