<HEAD>Expert: Recent Rains Limit Damage To Christmas Tree Industry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Recent rains have <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> tree growers dreaming of a green Christmas. The drought killed more than 10 million seedlings in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, but the rains should help keep Christmas tree prices about the same as last year, said <PERSON> Melvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Koelling </PERSON>, a forestry professor at <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` From the consumer standpoint, I do n't expect a change in quality, quantity or price this year,'' <PERSON> Koelling </PERSON> said Thursday. `` Retailers should n't use the drought as justification for price increases.'' <PERSON> Koelling </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> is the nation's biggest producer of Christmas trees, followed by <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> produced 55 million Christmas trees in 1987, and should be at or above that level this year, depending on demand. Millions of trees have been spared from drought damage since rains began in mid-July, <PERSON> Koelling </PERSON> said. `` Those rains came exactly when they had to come,'' <PERSON> Koelling </PERSON> said. `` We would have lost a significant number of large trees without the rains.'' Many trees up to 6 years old died, he said. Most Christmas trees are harvested after about 10 years' growth. Scotch pines, the mainstay of <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>'s Christmas tree crop, have fared better than fir trees, <PERSON> Koelling </PERSON> said.
